{"title_page": "COVID-19 pandemic in Pakistan", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Pakistan}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = COVID-19 pandemic in Pakistan\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Pakistan.png\n| legend1         = Map of confirmed cases by districts in Pakistan '''as of 28 April 2020'''\n{{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases}}\n| map2            = Punjab in Pakistan.svg\n| legend2         = Punjab remains the province with highest number of cases at over 7,100 '''as of 3 May 2020'''.\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Pakistan]]\n| first_case      = [[Karachi]]\n| arrival_date    = 26 February 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month=02|day=26|year=2020}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 20,084<ref name=\"govt tracker\"/>\n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 5,114<ref name=\"govt tracker\"/>\n| deaths          = 457<ref name=\"govt tracker\"/>\n| website         = [http://covid.gov.pk www.covid.gov.pk]\n}}\n\nThe [[COVID-19 pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Pakistan]] on 26 February 2020, when a student in [[Karachi]] tested positive upon returning from [[Iran]].<ref name=\"first\"/> By 18 March, cases had been registered in all four provinces, the two autonomous territories, and the federal territory of [[Islamabad Capital Territory|Islamabad]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus updates, March 18: Latest news on the coronavirus outbreak from Pakistan and around the world |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/277853-coronavirus-updates-march-18-latest-news-on-the-coronavirus-outbreak-from-pakistan-and-around-the-world |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=Geo News |archive-url= |archive-date= |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|05|03|post=,}} there have been <!-- use a round figure here, nearest to 100 --> over 19,100 confirmed cases with 4,315 recoveries and 385 deaths in the country. [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] has recorded the most cases at over <!-- use a round figure here, nearest to 100 --> 7,100, while [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] has reported the most deaths in the country, a total of 172.<ref name=\"govt tracker\">{{Cite web|url=http://covid.gov.pk/|title=Coronavirus in Pakistan - Confirmed Cases|website=www.covid.gov.pk/|accessdate=29 April 2020}}</ref> The country has been put under a nation-wide lockdown until 9 May,<ref name=\"lockdowns4\"/> which was initiated on 1 April and later extended twice.<ref name=\"lockdowns2\"/>\n\nAccording to a report by the federal government, Pakistan could have expected 50,000 cases of the disease by 25 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus updates, April 4: Latest news on the COVID-19 pandemic from Pakistan and around the world |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/280871-coronavirus-updates-april-4-latest-news-on-the-covid-19-pandemic-from-pakistan-and-around-the-world |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=www.geo.tv |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406150752/https://www.geo.tv/latest/280871-coronavirus-updates-april-4-latest-news-on-the-covid-19-pandemic-from-pakistan-and-around-the-world |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Number of cases expected to rise to 50,000 by April 25, govt tells Supreme Court |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/280938-govt-submits-report-on-national-action-plan-to-sc |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=www.geo.tv |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406170456/https://www.geo.tv/latest/280938-govt-submits-report-on-national-action-plan-to-sc |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=LIVE: PM Imran urges Pakistanis to be steadfast in their faith amid COVID-19 crisis |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2190581/1-live-new-cases-emerge-across-country-death-toll-reaches-40/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=The Express Tribune |date=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> However, the number by then remained under 13,000, less than half of what was expected.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus updates, April 25: Latest news on the COVID-19 pandemic from Pakistan and around the world |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/284832-coronavirus-updates-april-25-latest-news-on-the-covid-19-pandemic-from-pakistan-and-around-the-world |accessdate=26 April 2020 |work=Geo News |date=26 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> A [[2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Pakistan|Tablighi Jamaat religious congregation]] which took place in Lahore in early March 2020 became a coronavirus super-spreader,<ref name=\"Dawn/8April\" /> accounting for 27% of cases in the country by late April.<ref name=\"27percent\"/> Pakistan started vaccine trials in collaboration with [[Sinopharm]], a Chinese pharmaceutical company in April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=China has prepared a vaccine to treat COVID-19 patients and it would be launched in Pakistan in three months |url=https://rackpost.com/1620/china-has-prepared-a-vaccine-to-treat-covid-19-patients-and-it-would-be-launched-in-pakistan-in-three-months/ |website=Rackpost.com |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Main|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Pakistan}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Pakistan medical cases chart}}\n===February 2020===\nOn 26 February, Pakistan confirmed its first two cases of the coronavirus. [[Zafar Mirza]], the Prime Minister's Special Assistant on Health, stated in a [[Twitter|tweet]]: \"I can confirm first two cases of coronavirus in Pakistan. Both cases are being taken care of according to clinical standard protocols & both of them are stable.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/02/26/sindh-health-two-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-pakistan-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-in-karachi/|title=Two coronavirus cases confirmed in Pakistan - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|access-date=2020-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228064051/https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/02/26/sindh-health-two-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-pakistan-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-in-karachi/|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet| user=zfrmrza| number=1232707169163841537| first=Zafar| last=Mirza| title=I can confirm first two cases of coronavirus in Pakistan. Both cases are being taken care of according to clinical standard protocols & both of them are stable. No need to panic, things are under control. I will hold press conf tomorrow on return from Taftan.| date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first patient was a student at the [[University of Karachi]], [[Karachi]] in [[Sindh province]] while the second patient was from the federal territory of the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefrontierpost.com/two-more-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-pakistan/|title=Two more coronavirus cases confirmed in Pakistan|date=2020-02-29|website=The Frontier Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301143334/https://thefrontierpost.com/two-more-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-pakistan/|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Both patients had recently returned from [[Iran]].<ref name=\"first\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/pakistan-detects-first-coronavirus-cases-links-iran-outbreak|title=Pakistan Detects First Coronavirus Cases, Links to Iran Outbreak {{!}} Voice of America - English|website=www.voanews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306011154/https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/pakistan-detects-first-coronavirus-cases-links-iran-outbreak|archive-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arab.news/rawae|title=Pakistan prepares to fight back as two coronavirus cases emerge in country|date=2020-02-26|website=Arab News PK|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nWithin a week of the first two cases, Pakistan confirmed three more cases, including a case in Pakistan's capital, [[Islamabad]] and also in [[Rawalpindi]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/28-Feb-2020/3-coronavirus-cases-detected-in-rawalpindi|title=3 coronavirus cases detected in Rawalpindi|last=|first=|date=28 February 2020|website=nation.com.pk|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304153943/https://nation.com.pk/28-Feb-2020/3-coronavirus-cases-detected-in-rawalpindi|archive-date=4 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/international/world-news-politics/five-suspected-cases-of-coronavirus-reported-in-pakistan-803062.html|title=Five suspected cases of coronavirus reported in Pakistan|date=2020-02-09|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/world/panic-in-pakistan-after-fifth-confirmed-coronavirus-case/story/397468.html|title=Panic in Pakistan after fifth confirmed coronavirus case|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2020-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304160956/https://www.businesstoday.in/current/world/panic-in-pakistan-after-fifth-confirmed-coronavirus-case/story/397468.html|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\n\n==== March 1\u201310 \u2013 Early spread ====\nThe fifth case was also reported, on 2 March, from the federal area of the country,<ref>{{Cite news|agency=Reuters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/02/world/asia/02reuters-health-coronavirus-pakistan.html|title=Pakistan Confirms Fifth Coronavirus Case|date=2020-03-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bolnews.com/health/2020/03/panic-rises-in-pakistan-as-country-confirms-fifth-coronavirus-case/|title=Panic rises in Pakistan as country confirms fifth Coronavirus Case|date=2020-03-03|website=BOL News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> of a 45-year-old woman from [[Gilgit-Baltistan]], who had also travelled from Iran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arab.news/b5hqz|title=Pakistan confirms fifth coronavirus case|date=2020-03-03|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, [[Murtaza Wahab]] announced that the first patient in Karachi had fully recovered and was later discharged from hospital after testing negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/624788-pakistans-first-coronavirus-patient-recovers-tests-negative-murtaza-wahab|title=Pakistan's first coronavirus patient recovers, tests 'negative': Murtaza Wahab|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309081127/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/624788-pakistans-first-coronavirus-patient-recovers-tests-negative-murtaza-wahab|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/pakistan-confirms-7th-coronavirus-case/1758933|title=Pakistan confirms 7th coronavirus case|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309151959/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/pakistan-confirms-7th-coronavirus-case/1758933|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 March, Pakistan confirmed its seventh case of COVID-19, also in Karachi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2171931/1-fourth-coronavirus-case-surfaces-karachi-tally-hits-7-country/|title=Pakistan's 7th coronavirus case surfaces in Karachi|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2020-03-08|website=The Express Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312035400/https://tribune.com.pk/story/2171931/1-fourth-coronavirus-case-surfaces-karachi-tally-hits-7-country/|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe next day, Pakistan reported nine new cases in Karachi, meaning that there was a total of 16 cases of COVID-19, with Sindh having the highest number of cases, 13 altogether.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2172615/1-5th-coronavirus-case-emerges-karachi-tally-soars-8-pakistan/|title=Nine new coronavirus cases emerge in Karachi as Pakistan's tally jumps to 16|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2020-03-09|website=The Express Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312081955/https://tribune.com.pk/story/2172615/1-5th-coronavirus-case-emerges-karachi-tally-soars-8-pakistan/|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Five of the new patients had travelled to [[Syria]] and some others patients had returned from [[London]]. Three new cases were confirmed on 10 March, including one in [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]] and the first case in [[Quetta]], [[Balochistan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/pakistan-records-11-new-coronavirus-cases-bringing-the-total-tally-to-18-1.70279643|title=Pakistan records 11 new coronavirus cases bringing the total tally to 18|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310124434/https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/pakistan-records-11-new-coronavirus-cases-bringing-the-total-tally-to-18-1.70279643|archive-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/276505-coronavirus-updates-latest-news-on-the-coronavirus-outbreak-from-pakistan-and-around-the-world|title=Coronavirus updates: Latest news on the coronavirus outbreak from Pakistan and around the world|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311142207/https://www.geo.tv/latest/276505-coronavirus-updates-latest-news-on-the-coronavirus-outbreak-from-pakistan-and-around-the-world|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 11\u201319 \u2013 Outbreak ====\nOn 11 March, 76 suspected cases were reported in several districts of Punjab province, including [[Lahore]], [[Gujranwala]], [[Sargodha]], [[Hafizabad]] and [[Lodhran]]. The Healthcare Department officials informed that ten patients were immediately cleared of the suspicion, while 55 patients were cleared after testing negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/627575-76-suspected-coronavirus-patients-reported-in-punjab|title=76 suspected coronavirus patients reported in Punjab|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en-PK|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311122749/https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/627575-76-suspected-coronavirus-patients-reported-in-punjab|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A second case in [[Gilgit-Baltistan]] was confirmed the same day in [[Skardu]] leaving the tally at 20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/627631-gilgit-baltistan-reports-second-case-pakistan-tally-rises-to-20|title=Pakistan's tally of coronavirus rises to 20 as second case emerges in Gilgit Baltistan|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311150855/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/627631-gilgit-baltistan-reports-second-case-pakistan-tally-rises-to-20|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A third case was confirmed in Gilgit-Baltistan in [[Shigar District|Shigar district]] on 12 March, who had a travel history of Iran and was reported to be under treatment at the Skardu hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/628096-coronavirus-cases-in-pakistan-rise-to-21-after-gb-reports-third-case|title=Coronavirus cases in Pakistan rise to 21 after GB reports third case|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312174016/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/628096-coronavirus-cases-in-pakistan-rise-to-21-after-gb-reports-third-case|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, [[Murtaza Wahab]] informed that the second patient of the virus had completely recovered.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} On 13 March, the Sindh Health Department identified a 52-year-old patient as positive, which marked the first case of local disease transmission as the patient had travelled from [[Islamabad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawnnews.tv/news/1122234|title=First locally transmitted case of coronavirus|website=www.dawnnews.tv|date=13 March 2020|language=Urdu|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314135121/https://www.dawnnews.tv/news/1122234/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SindhHealthDpt/status/1238325888145555457|title=#CoronaVirusPakistan|website=www.twitter.com/SindhHealthDpt|language=English|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313061146/https://twitter.com/SindhHealthDpt/status/1238325888145555457|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 24 of the 27 suspected cases in [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber Pakhtunkwa]] were also cleared that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/13-Mar-2020/24-out-of-27-suspcted-coronavirus-cases-cleared-in-kpk|title=24/27 KPK|last=|first=|date=13 March 2020|website=www.nation.com.pk|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313191600/https://nation.com.pk/13-Mar-2020/24-out-of-27-suspcted-coronavirus-cases-cleared-in-kpk|archive-date=13 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> At the end of the day, the total number of cases had risen to 28, with six new cases in [[Taftan, Balochistan|Taftan]] and another in Sindh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/277182-pakistan-has-28-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-dr-zafar-mirza|title=Dr Zafar Mirza confirms 28 coronavirus cases in Pakistan|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314151403/https://www.geo.tv/latest/277182-pakistan-has-28-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-dr-zafar-mirza|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-14-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=20 March 2020|date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320185333/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-14-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 14 March, the number of cases was 31 as two new patients were found positive in Karachi while one was reported in Islamabad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/277293-islamabad-reports-first-coronavirus-case-tally-rises-to-29|title=Another coronavirus patient emerges in Sindh, Pakistan's affected toll rises to 31|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315135737/https://www.geo.tv/latest/277293-islamabad-reports-first-coronavirus-case-tally-rises-to-29|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFive more cases were announced in Karachi the next day on 15 March, including a second local transmission of the coronavirus in Sindh, while the other three had a travel history of [[Saudi Arabia]] and one had been to Balochistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=684671|title=Coronavirus cases in Pak reaches 33|website=www.daijiworld.com|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326031106/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx%3FnewsID%3D684671|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There was also a new case reported in [[Islamabad Capital Territory]]. Lahore Health Secretary, Mohammad Usman confirmed the first case of coronavirus in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] in the city of [[Lahore]]. The infected patient had returned from [[United Kingdom]] on 10 March and was shifted to Mayo Hospital in an isolation ward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/pakistan-records-spike-in-number-of-coronavirus-cases-as-the-government-takes-preventive-measures-1.70403993|title=Pakistan records spike in number of coronavirus cases as the government takes preventive measures|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315164329/https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/pakistan-records-spike-in-number-of-coronavirus-cases-as-the-government-takes-preventive-measures-1.70403993|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[National Institute of Health (Pakistan)|National Institute of Health]] reported 11 new cases in Sindh and 6 new in a mobile lab at the Taftan border area. and the first case in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], increasing the tally to 53.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-16-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=20 March 2020|date=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317064911/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-16-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/living/health/2020/03/pakistan-coronavirus-tally/|title=Pakistan coronavirus tally reaches 53 {{!}} SAMAA|website=Samaa TV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316213048/https://www.samaa.tv/living/health/2020/03/pakistan-coronavirus-tally/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 March, a total of 134 new positives cases were registered, the majority of them, 116 in Sindh. Khyber Pakhtunkhwa also reported its first 15 cases<ref>{{cite news|url=https://arynews.tv/en/coronavirus-cases-kp-province-taimur-jhagra/|title=First 15 cases of coronavirus reported in KP province: Taimur Jhagra|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317145936/https://arynews.tv/en/coronavirus-cases-kp-province-taimur-jhagra/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while 3 were found in Balochistan. This marked the sharpest increase so far as not only were more than a 100 cases were reported in a province within a day but also the number across the country reached 187.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-17-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=20 March 2020|date=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320185344/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-17-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/277536-pakistans-coronavirus-tally-crosses-100-as-sindh-reports-88-cases|title=Coronavirus tally crosses 130; Sindh reports sharp increase, KP reports first cases|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317145539/https://www.geo.tv/latest/277536-pakistans-coronavirus-tally-crosses-100-as-sindh-reports-88-cases|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/coronavirus-case-186-pakistan-more-likely-come-up/story/398382.html|title=Coronavirus cases shoot up to 186 in Pakistan; more likely to come up|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318172141/https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/coronavirus-case-186-pakistan-more-likely-come-up/story/398382.html|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The tally had shot up to 237 with 25 new cases in Punjab, 12 in Sindh and 4 in Islamabad on 17 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2177847/1-10-new-covid-19-cases-confirmed-as-pakistans-tally-hits-194/|title=237|last=|first=|date=17 March 2020|website=tribune.com.pk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-18-Mar-2020-1.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=18 March 2020|date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318063435/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-18-Mar-2020-1.pdf|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Daily21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-21-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=21 March 2020|date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321050026/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-21-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy 18 March, the first case of coronavirus was reported from [[Azad Kashmir]]. The provinces of Sindh and Gilgit-Baltistan saw an increase of cases by 36 and 10 respectively. New cases were also reported in other provinces. A patient from [[Hyderabad]] was also discharged after recovering in Sindh province, making the total number of recovered cases 5. A total of 302 positive cases were confirmed in Pakistan on 18 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-19-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=19 March 2020|date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319075847/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-19-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/277853-coronavirus-updates-march-18-latest-news-on-the-coronavirus-outbreak-from-pakistan-and-around-the-world|title=Coronavirus updates, March 18: Latest news on the coronavirus outbreak from Pakistan and around the world|website=www.geo.tv|date=18 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321075725/https://www.geo.tv/latest/277853-coronavirus-updates-march-18-latest-news-on-the-coronavirus-outbreak-from-pakistan-and-around-the-world|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first two deaths due to the virus in the country were also confirmed on the day. Both were reported from the province of [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]], the first being a 50-year-old man who had recently from [[Saudi Arabia]] to [[Mardan District]] after performing [[Umrah]] in [[Mecca]], while the second victim was a 36-year-old from [[Hangu District, Pakistan|Hangu District]]. Both had been hospitalised in [[Peshawar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/277989-one-patient-passes-away-in-mardan-kp-health-minister-jhagra|title=Pakistan confirms two deaths from coronavirus|website=www.geo.tv|date=18 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321074541/https://www.geo.tv/latest/277989-one-patient-passes-away-in-mardan-kp-health-minister-jhagra|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe cases doubled by more than half from 33 to 80 in Punjab; and from 23 to 81 in Balochistan on 19 March. The rise in cases led the provincial government of Balochistan to declare a health emergency and impose a ban on public transport. The provincial government spokesperson Liaquat Shahwani stated that a relief package will be provided to the employees of transport companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2179414/1-pakistans-coronavirus-tally-reaches-330-new-cases-emerge-k-p-sindh/|title=March 19: Pakistan's coronavirus cases jump to 454|website=www.tribune.com.pk|date=19 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319225737/https://tribune.com.pk/story/2179414/1-pakistans-coronavirus-tally-reaches-330-new-cases-emerge-k-p-sindh/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> With a total of 159 new cases, the number confirmed cases jumped to 461.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-20-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=20 March 2020|date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320110819/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-20-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 20\u201331 \u2013 First deaths  ====\nOn 20 March, the first death was reported in Sindh. The patient was a 77-year-old who had acquired the virus through local transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2180094/1-sindh-reports-first-coronavirus-related-death/|title=Sindh reports first coronavirus-related death|website=www.tribune.com.pk|date=20 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> The patient was a cancer survivor and had other underlying medical problems such as [[hypertension]] and [[diabetes]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/pakistan-reports-730-active-coronavirus-cases-shuts-all-international-flights/story/398878.html|title=Pakistan reports 730 active coronavirus cases; shuts all international flights|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322085915/https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/pakistan-reports-730-active-coronavirus-cases-shuts-all-international-flights/story/398878.html|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> While in other provinces, the increase in number of new cases was lower compared to the past few days at 34 and the tally stood at 495.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-03-April-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=3 April 2020|date=2 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407232055/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-03-April-2020.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the third death in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa was announced. The first death in Gilgit-Baltistan and Balochistan were also announced on that day, meaning that the number of deaths increased to 6. The number of cases had also increased to 784 with 138 new cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/coronavirus-pakistan-reports-4th-death-due-to-covid-19-on-sunday-as-the-country-heads-towards-lockdown-1.70552122|title=Coronavirus: Pakistan reports 4th death due to COVID-19 on Sunday as the country heads towards lockdown|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322131837/https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/coronavirus-pakistan-reports-4th-death-due-to-covid-19-on-sunday-as-the-country-heads-towards-lockdown-1.70552122|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/278713-pakistan-reports-sixth-death-from-coronavirus-number-of-confirmed-cases-rise-to|title=Pakistan reports sixth death from coronavirus, number of confirmed cases rise to 803|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323081407/https://www.geo.tv/latest/278713-pakistan-reports-sixth-death-from-coronavirus-number-of-confirmed-cases-rise-to|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The fatality at [[DHQ Hospital Gilgit|DHQ Hospital]] in [[Gilgit]] was a doctor who contracted the virus after screening pilgrims returning from Iran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/22-Mar-2020/pakistan-s-fifth-coronavirus-death-confirmed-in-gilgit-baltistan|title=Pakistan's fifth Coronavirus death confirmed in Gilgit Baltistan|date=2020-03-22|website=The Nation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151715/https://nation.com.pk/22-Mar-2020/pakistan-s-fifth-coronavirus-death-confirmed-in-gilgit-baltistan|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/278684-gb-doctor-passes-away|title=Doctor who led fight against coronavirus in Gilgit-Baltistan passes away|date=2020-03-22|website=Geo News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323122834/https://www.geo.tv/latest/278684-gb-doctor-passes-away|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 22 March, Gilgit-Baltistan went under lockdown for an indefinite period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radio.gov.pk/22-03-2020/gb-govt-decides-to-observe-lockdown-for-indefinite-period|title=GB Govt decides to observe lockdown for indefinite period|website=www.radio.gov.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323083737/http://www.radio.gov.pk/22-03-2020/gb-govt-decides-to-observe-lockdown-for-indefinite-period|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 13 new pilgrims from [[Taftan, Balochistan|Taftan]] via [[Dera Ghazi Khan]] were put in [[quarantine]] at [[Mirpur, Pakistan|Mirpur]]. Also on that day, [[Descon|DESCON]] donated 10,000 [[Hand sanitizer|hand sanitisers]] to hospitals in Punjab, whereas in Balochistan 26 drivers who transported the positive COVID-19 cases to hospitals were kept in quarantine.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-23-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|date=23 March 2020|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323055757/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-23-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, many doctors across the nation complained about the lack of proper equipment for battling the virus. A spokesman for Doctors' Union in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa said, \"We do not have [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE), or [[goggles]], and even [[Surgical mask|[face] masks]] we are buying from our own funds\".<ref name=\"doctors complain\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/pakistani-doctors-decry-lack-supplies-lockdown-debate-rages-200323110940130.html|title=Pakistani doctors decry lack of supplies as lockdown looms|website=aljazeera.com|date=23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324103014/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/pakistani-doctors-decry-lack-supplies-lockdown-debate-rages-200323110940130.html|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Arrangements were made on the day by the [[Foreign Office of Pakistan|Foreign Office]] to bring 72 Pakistanis stranded at the [[Doha International Airport]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]] as it had decided to temporarily ban travelers from Pakistan and 14 other countries early in the month. The passengers were subject to strict screening upon arrival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/23/pakistanis-stranded-at-qatar-airport-to-be-brought-home-tonight/|title=Pakistanis stranded at Qatar airport to be brought home tonight|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|date=23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324095440/https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/23/pakistanis-stranded-at-qatar-airport-to-be-brought-home-tonight/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Another flight was arranged to bring 150 citizens for the [[United Arab Emirates|UAE]] stranded at [[Dubai International Airport|Dubai]] and [[Abu Dhabi International Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arynews.tv/en/pakistanis-stranded-uae-brought-back/|title=Pakistanis stranded in UAE to be brought back via special flight|website=www.arynews.tv|date=23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324145656/https://arynews.tv/en/pakistanis-stranded-uae-brought-back/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Sindh Education Minister [[Saeed Ghani]] tested positive for the virus and self-quarrantined for 14 days that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arynews.tv/en/sindh-minister-saeed-ghani-tests-positive-for-coronaviru/|title=Sindh Education Minister Saeed Ghani tests positive for coronavirus|website=www.arynews.tv|date=23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324153749/https://arynews.tv/en/sindh-minister-saeed-ghani-tests-positive-for-coronaviru/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He recovered from the virus on 30 March.<ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1545038/sindh-minister-saeed-ghani-recovers-from-coronavirus Sindh minister Saeed Ghani recovers from coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331235110/https://www.dawn.com/news/1545038/sindh-minister-saeed-ghani-recovers-from-coronavirus |date=31 March 2020 }}, Dawn, 30 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, Sindh and Balochistan observed lockdown until 7 April, while Azad Kahmsir went under it until 13 April respectively.<ref name=\"sindh lockdown\"/><ref name=\"balochistan lockdown\"/><ref name=\"ajk lockdown\"/> Punjab also imposed lockdown on 24 March, but only until 6 April.<ref name=\"punjab lockdown\"/> In Sindh, the local police detained 472 people in various districts of the province the same day in violation of the lockdown, with 222 of them in Karachi alone and a total of 72 FIRs were registered on 24 March. The cases pertained to hoarding and profiteering of safety masks and hand sanitisers, large gatherings, opening shops and restaurants and travelling in passenger buses.<ref name=\"lockdown arrests\"/> The provincial government of Sindh allowed 640 pilgrims quarantined in Sukkur to return home after being tested negative for the virus. The Chief Minister issued directives for the relevant deputy commissioners to receive the pilgrims on their return and monitor their health conditions for the next 10 days.<ref name=\"pilgrims return\">{{cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2183538/1-homecoming-last-640-pilgrims-cleared-infection-return-home-sukkur/|title=Homecoming at last: 640 pilgrims cleared of infection to return home from Sukkur|date=25 March 2020|work=ARY News|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, several restrictions were imposed in the capital territory of Islamabad. These included closing of the outpatient departments of hospitals, complete bans on intra-city, inter-district and inter-province public transport as well as gatherings in public and private places.<ref name=\"islamabad measures\"/> Three new recoveries were announced as well as the eighth death in the country. The number of positive cases in the nation crossed 1,000 as the tally increased to 1,057.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-26-Mar-2020.pdf|title=NIH Daily Report 26 March|date=25 March 2020|website=nih.org.pk|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326080315/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-26-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 March, 140 new cases were tested positive across Pakistan. One new death was reported in Punjab, meaning that the death toll increased to 9. The total number of cases reached 1,197. Meanwhile, the number of recoveries increased by 2.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-27-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|date=27 March 2020|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327075701/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-27-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Pakistan reported a total of 211 new cases, the first time the number crossed 200. Punjab also overtook Sindh as the province with highest number of cases at 490, while two deaths were also reported there.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2185974/1/ Punjab overtakes Sindh in virus cases] The Express Tribune, 28 March 2020</ref> The [[National Institute of Health, Islamabad|National Institute of Health]] (NIH) distributed [[N95 mask]]s across Sindh, while in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, screeing teams were deputed at all district entry and exit points for screening of visitors of Covid-19 patients. In Gilgit-Baltistan, the local government decided that all travellers coming from the Taftan border would be tested for COVID-19. The total number of positive cases in the country reach 1408, while 3 patients were discharged, making the recovered cases a total of 26 and two deaths occurred, taking the total number of deaths to 11.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-28-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|date=28 March 2020|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328092723/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-28-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The NIH initiated district level trainings of [[high-dependency unit]], isolation and quarantine staff across Punjab.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC7\"/>\n\nOn 28 March, the Foundation set up by the Chinese billionaire [[Jack Ma]] and the [[Alibaba Group]] sent a second aircraft carrying various medical supplies to Pakistan. The aircraft was received in Karachi with at least 50,000 testing kits, large number of face masks, ventilators and [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE), which were combined around two tonnes of supplies worth Rs67 million.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2186088/1-china-sends-another-aircraft-carrying-medical-supplies-pakistan/ China sends another aircraft carrying medical supplies to Pakistan] The Express Tribune, 28 March 2020</ref> The same day, Pakistan allowed [[Thai Airways]] to resume its flight operation for Islamabad to bring back 175 Pakistanis stranded in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]].<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2186118/3/ Special Thai Airways flight to bring back stranded Pakistanis] The Express Tribune, 28 March 2020</ref> Meanwhile, the Government of Punjab announced a Rs10 billion relief package for financial support of 2.5 million families of daily-wage earners.<ref name=\"punjab relief\"/>\n\nThe country reported an additional 118 cases on 29 March, taking the total to 1,526. One death each was reported in the provinces of Sindh and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, taking the total number of deceased to 13. Khyber Pakhtunkhwa developed and disseminated quarantine discontinuation guidelines.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-29-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|date=29 March 2020|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=30 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074650/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-29-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Also on the day, five Pakistani nationals visiting India on medical visas returned home via the [[Wagah border]] after being stranded in [[Noida]] and [[New Delhi]] due to the countrywide 21-day lockdown imposed by the Indian government.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2186906/1-five-pakistanis-stranded-india-return-via-wagah-border/ Five Pakistanis stranded in India return via Wagah border], The Express Tribune, 29 March 2020</ref> Two of them tested positive for the virus on 31 March.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2188079/1-two-pakistani-nationals-test-positive-covid-19-returning-india/ Two Pakistani nationals test positive for COVID-19 after returning from India], The Express Tribune, 31 March 2020</ref> As the cases neared 500 in Sindh, the CM of the province said that the data showed 25% of cases were due to local transmission. He stated,  \"the local transmission ratio is worrisome and needs to be contained further.\"<ref>[https://nation.com.pk/29-Mar-2020/17-new-covid-19-cases-of-local-transmission-surface-in-karachi 17 new COVID-19 cases of local transmission surface in Karachi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331054317/https://nation.com.pk/29-Mar-2020/17-new-covid-19-cases-of-local-transmission-surface-in-karachi |date=31 March 2020 }}, The Nation, 29 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Pakistan reported the highest number of new cases in a single day for March at 240. The total number reached 1,865 while total recoveries stood at 58 with 25 deaths.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-31-Mar-2020.pdf|title=COVID-19 Daily Situation Report \u2013 NIH Pakistan|date=30 March 2020|website=www.nih.org.pk/|access-date=30 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407232106/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-31-Mar-2020.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the Federal Minister for Science and Technology [[Chaudhry Fawad Hussain]] said that locally manufactured ventilators and testing kits would hit the market in the coming days. The coronavirus testing kits were developed by Pakistan's [[National University of Sciences and Technology, Pakistan|National University of Sciences & Technology]] (NUST) have been handed to the [[Ministry of National Health Services, Regulation and Coordination#Drug Regulatory Authority of Pakistan|Drug Regulatory Authority]] (DRAP) for final approval. While the [[Pakistan Engineering Council]] (PEC) developed ventilators, in collaboration with [[NED University of Engineering and Technology]] and Pakistan Engineering Board, which were handed over to DRAP later in the week. He also said that the capacity of [[Pakistan Council of Scientific and Industrial Research]] (PCSIR) for production of hand sanitizers was enhanced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2020/03/30/584835/pakistani-manufactured-coronavirus-testing-kits-ventilators-to-hit-markets-soon/|title=Pakistani manufactured coronavirus testing kits, ventilators to hit markets soon|date=30 March 2020|website=www.brecorder.com|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, 82 total recoveries were announced, as well as the 26th death in the country. 174 new cases were tested positive, meaning that the total number of positive cases had increased to 2,039.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-01-April-2020.pdf|title=NIH 01/04/20|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407232107/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-01-April-2020.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April, 252 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of cases to 2291, while the total number of recoveries in the country surpassed 100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/COVID-19-DailyUpdatedSitRepNew02-April-2020-1.pdf|title=NIH 02/04/20|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nih.org.pk/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407232054/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/COVID-19-DailyUpdatedSitRepNew02-April-2020-1.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> A further 159 new cases were confirmed on 2 April, bringing the tally to 2450. Four deaths were reported, two from Sindh and one each from KP, and Gilgit increasing the total to 35.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-03-April-2020.pdf|title=NIH 03/04/20|website=www.nih.org.pk/|accessdate=3 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407232055/https://www.nih.org.pk/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/COVID-19-Daily-Updated-SitRep-03-April-2020.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The total cases increased to 2708 after 258 new cases were confirmed on 3 April, making Ounjab the first province to cross 1,000 confirmed cases. Five deaths were reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arynews.tv/en/covid-19-cases-rise-to-2708-in-pakistan|title=Number of COVID-19 cases rise to 2,708 in Pakistan|date=4 April 2020|publisher=ARY News|accessdate=4 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406175340/https://arynews.tv/en/covid-19-cases-rise-to-2708-in-pakistan/|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/pakistan-records-2700-coronavirus-cases-punjab-crosses-1000-mark/articleshow/74979582.cms Pakistan records 2,700 coronavirus cases; Punjab crosses 1,000 mark], Times of India, 4 April 2020</ref>\n\nThe number of confirmed cases crossed 3,000 around the nation on 5 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweekpakistan.com/pakistans-coronavirus-cases-cross-3000/|title=Pakistan's Coronavirus Cases Cross 3,000|work=Newsweek|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407195221/https://www.newsweekpakistan.com/pakistans-coronavirus-cases-cross-3000/|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The country recorded nearly a 1000 cases over the next two days and the tally reached a total of 4,005 on 7 April with 54 deaths and 429 recoveries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/world/coronavirus-cases-cross-4000-in-pakistan-with-death-toll-at-54/397149/|title=Coronavirus cases cross 4,000 in Pakistan with death toll at 54|publisher=The Print|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407195219/https://theprint.in/world/coronavirus-cases-cross-4000-in-pakistan-with-death-toll-at-54/397149/|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Sindh became the second province to cross 1,000 confirmed cases after Punjab on 8 April.<ref>[https://www.brecorder.com/2020/04/08/587532/sindh-reports-2-more-deaths-coronavirus-cases-jump-to-1036/ Sindh reports 2 more deaths, coronavirus cases jump to 1036], Business Recorder, 8 April 2020</ref> On 11 April, the total cases surged over 5,000 leaving over 80 dead so far.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arynews.tv/en/coronavirus-cases-pakistan-dead/|title=Coronavirus cases jump above 5000 in Pakistan, 77 dead|last=|first=|date=|website=www.arynews.tv/|url-status=live|archive-date=11 April 2020|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/pak-to-take-decision-on-lockdown-on-monday-as-coronavirus-cases-cross-5-000-mark-120041200001_1.html|title=Pak to take decision on lockdown on Monday as coronavirus cases cross 5,000 mark|last=|first=|date=|website=www.arynews.tv/|url-status=live|archive-date=12 April 2020|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> The total number of recoveries in Pakistan reached abover 1,000 on 12 April.<ref>[https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/pakistan-awaits-clinical-trials-for-covid-19-treatment/1802977 Pakistan awaits clinical trials for COVID-19 treatment], Anadolu Agency, 13 April 2020</ref>\n\nThe federal government decided on 14 April to extend the ongoing lockdown for two more weeks until 30 April.<ref name=\"lockdowns3\"/> On 15 April, the national death tally surpassed 100 and the number of cases crossed 6000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-pakistans-cases-near-6-000-deaths-top-100/1805422|title=COVID-19: Pakistan's cases near 6,000, deaths top 100|last=Sajid|first=Islamuddin|date=15 April 2020|work=Anadolu Agency|url-status=live|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/pakistan/pakistan-extends-lockdown-as-covid-19-cases-cross-6000/articleshow/75160547.cms|title=Pakistan extends lockdown as Covid-19 cases cross 6,000|date=15 April 2020|work=The Times of India|url-status=live|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> On 16 April, it was reported that 58% of the cases had been locally transmitted in Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1549680|title=58pc of Pakistan's coronavirus cases are now locally transmitted|last=Junaidi|first=Ikram|date=2020-04-16|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nKhyber Pakhtunkhwa crossed the mark of 1,000 confirmed cases on 18 April.<ref>[https://menafn.com/1100043849/Pakistan-Coronavirus-cases-in-KP-cross-1000 Pakistan- Coronavirus cases in KP cross 1,000], MENAFN, 18 April 2020</ref> A report released on 21 April stated that over 2,000; 27% of the total positive cases in the country were linked to the religious congregation of the Tablighi Jamaat.<ref name=\"27percent\"/>\n\nPakistan crossed a critical mark of the outbreak in the country as the total number of cases surged above 10,000 on 22 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wionews.com/pakistan/coronavirus-cases-cross-10000-in-pakistan-294058|title=Coronavirus cases cross 10,000 in Pakistan|date=2020-04-22|website=wionews.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> On 24 April, the federal government once again extended the lockdown in the country, this time until 9 May.<ref name=\"lockdowns4\">{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2206167/1-countrywide-lockdown-stretched-till-may-9/|title=Countrywide lockdown stretched till May 9|last=Shehzad|first=Rizwan|work=The Express Tribune|language=en|date=2020-04-24|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\nIn late April a group of senior doctors in Pakistan, and abroad, wrote to religious leaders and to the prime minister \"pleading\" not to open mosques during [[ramadan]], particularly as 80% of the people attending would be mostly in their 60s and 70s.  This could result in an \"explosion of Covid-19\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gulftoday.ae/news/2020/04/22/pakistani-doctors-warn-of-catastrophe-if-mosques-remain-open  |title=Pakistani doctors warn of catastrophe if mosques remain open during Ramadan |date=22 April 2020|work=[[Gulf Today]]|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe governor of Sindh, Imran Ismail revealed on 27 April that he had tested positive for COVID-19 via [[twitter]].<ref>[https://www.geo.tv/latest/285270-governor-sindh-imran-ismail-tests-positive-for-covid-19 Governor Sindh Imran Ismail tests positive for COVID-19], Geo News, 27 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Raiwind Hotspot==\n{{See also|2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Pakistan}}\n[[Raiwind]] in the city of Lahore acts as the headquarters of the [[Tablighi Jamaat]] in Pakistan, an evangelical organisation that promotes proselytism by all its members. According to scholar [[Barbara Metcalf]], the annual congregation at Raiwind attracts some two million and odd attendees.<ref>{{citation |last=Metcalf |first=Barbara D. |title=Islam in South Asia in Practice |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pR0LzVCpfw8C |year=2009 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-1-4008-3138-8 |p=240\u2013241}}</ref> The Tablighi Jamaat congregations are popular with Muslims of other sects and also cuts across socio-economic classes, ranging from high-level politicians to the middle and lower classes.<ref name=Siddiqa>\nAyesha Siddiqa, [https://theprint.in/opinion/pakistan-tablighi-jamaat-covid-19-problem-blame-imran-khan-as-well/394229/ Like India, Pakistan has a Tablighi Jamaat Covid-19 problem too. But blame Imran Khan as well], The Print, 3 April 2020.\n</ref> On 10 March, a congregation of the organisation took place in [[Raiwind Markaz]] and resulted as a coronavirus super-spreader event with more than 539 confirmed cases linked to it reported across the country so far.<ref name=\"Dawn/8April\" />\n\nAccording to a report by the Punjab Special Branch approximately 70,000 to 80,000 members may have attended the congregation, with the majority being from various parts of Pakistan and 3,000 attendees from 40 foreign countries. The Jamaat's management claimed 250,000 attendees. The event carried on despite the strong opposition and warnings by the Government of Punjab. But according to the police, it was cut short from six days to three days.<ref name=\"Dawn/8April\">{{cite news |last1=Chaudhry |first1=Asif |title=Tableeghi Jamaat in hot water in Pakistan too for Covid-19 spread |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1547354 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=DAWN |date=8 April 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408041910/https://www.dawn.com/news/1547354 |archive-date=8 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=250,000 Ijtimah in Raiwind despite coronavirus warnings - Pakistan Today |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/13/250000-ijtimah-raiwind-despite-coronavirus-warnings/ |newspaper=Pakistan Today |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=9 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402003238/https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/13/250000-ijtimah-raiwind-despite-coronavirus-warnings/ |archive-date=2 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A cluster spread became apparent in the following days as cases traced back to the event were reported across the country.<ref name=\"Firstpost/8April\"/> By 31 March, 143 infections and three deaths were reported.<ref name=\"Reuters/31March\">Reuters, [https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/31/world/asia/31reuters-health-coronavirus-southasia.html?searchResultPosition=10 India and Pakistan Crack Down on Muslim Group Emerging as COVID-19 Cluster], The New York Times, 31 March 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, Pakistani authorities placed the entire city of Raiwind under quarantine, and shut down all general and medical stores after 40 Tablighi Jamaat participants tested positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan places Raiwind under complete lockdown after Tablighi Jamaat members tested coronavirus positive |url=https://www.deccanherald.com/international/pakistan-places-raiwind-under-complete-lockdown-after-tablighi-jamaat-members-tested-coronavirus-positive-820433.html |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Deccan Herald |date=2 April 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406011117/https://www.deccanherald.com/international/pakistan-places-raiwind-under-complete-lockdown-after-tablighi-jamaat-members-tested-coronavirus-positive-820433.html |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 8 April, 539 infections were reported, of which 404 were in the Raiwind Markaz and 31 in [[Hafizabad]].<ref name=\"Dawn/8April\"/>\n\nIn [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], 10,263 attendees of the Tablighi Jamaat event were quarantined in 36 districts of the province. Efforts are under way to trace thousands of other participants.<ref name=\"Dawn/8April\"/> The government of [[Sindh]] also announced a quarantine of all the attendees of the  event. Bara Kahu in [[Islamabad]] has been quarantined as some returning attendees there tested positive for the coronavirus.<ref name=Siddiqa/> Approximately 50 participants of the Tablighi Jamaat, including five Nigerian women, were admitted to a quarantine centre in [[Kasur]] while some 38 participants have also tested positive in [[Hyderabad, Pakistan|Hyderabad]].<ref name=\"Firstpost/8April\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Pakistan places Raiwind city under complete lockdown after 40 Tablighi Jamaat preachers test positive |url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-pakistan-places-raiwind-city-under-complete-lockdown-after-40-tablighi-jamaat-preachers-test-positive-8220201.html |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Firstpost}}</ref>\n\nA report in late April revealed that the event had caused over 2,000; 27% of the country's total positive cases.<ref name=\"27percent\">{{cite news |title=27% of Pakistan's Covid-19 cases linked to Raiwind Ijtima: report |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2203599/9-27-pakistans-covid-19-cases-linked-raiwind-ijtima-report/ |accessdate=21 April 2020 |work=The Express Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==Other cases==\nOn 29 January, four Pakistani students studying in [[China]] tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]. Two more were later confirmed making the total number 6. Four of the students had recovered on 12 February while the other two recovered on 14 February after being hospitalised in [[Guangzhou]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/276711-a-timeline-of-the-emergence-of-the-coronavirus-in-pakistan|title=A timeline of the spread of coronavirus in Pakistan|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|date=11 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311202854/https://www.geo.tv/latest/276711-a-timeline-of-the-emergence-of-the-coronavirus-in-pakistan|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, the [[List of diplomatic missions of Pakistan|Pakistani consulate]] in [[Milan]] announced the first death of a Pakistani from COVID-19 in [[Brescia]], [[Italy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/627660-coronavirus-one-pakistani-in-italy-dies-of-the-epidemic|title=Coronavirus: One Pakistani in Italy dies of the epidemic|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322203513/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/627660-coronavirus-one-pakistani-in-italy-dies-of-the-epidemic|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA Pakistani national tested positive at the [[Torkham|Torkham border]] between Pakistan and Afghanistan on 12 March. It was reported that the patient was an employee of [[List of diplomatic missions of Pakistan|Pakistani embassy]] in Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/12-Mar-2020/two-test-positive-for-coronavirus-at-torkham-border-including-one-pakistani-national|title=Two test positive for coronavirus at Torkham border, including a Pakistani national|website=www.nation.com.pk|date=12 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313153229/https://nation.com.pk/12-Mar-2020/two-test-positive-for-coronavirus-at-torkham-border-including-one-pakistani-national|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, the Palestinian Health Ministry announced a new case in [[Salfit Governorate]], [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], which originated from [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://pnn.ps/news/498848 | title=\u0648\u0632\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u062d\u0629: \u0625\u0635\u0627\u0628\u0629 \u062c\u062f\u064a\u062f\u0629 \u0628\u0633\u0644\u0641\u064a\u062a\u2026 \u0648\u0634\u0641\u0627\u0621 17 \u0645\u0631\u064a\u0636\u064b\u0627 \u0643\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0627 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0641\u0646\u062f\u0642 \"\u0622\u0646\u062c\u0644\" \u0628\u0628\u064a\u062a \u0644\u062d\u0645 | access-date=25 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321151753/http://pnn.ps/news/498848 | archive-date=21 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=j3upWja115452397665aj3upWj|title=Palestine confirms new coronavirus case, recovery of 17 others|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020|publisher=WAFA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404065814/http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=j3upWja115452397665aj3upWj|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 March, Palestinian sources confirmed the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the State of Palestine|first two cases]] in [[Gaza City]], [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]]; the two Palestinians had traveled from Pakistan and entered Gaza through [[Egypt]]. Once they had tested positive for the virus they were placed in quarantine in [[Rafah]] since their arrival on 19 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-corona-palestinians-gaza/first-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-the-palestinian-gaza-strip-idUSKBN219004|title=First coronavirus cases confirmed in the Palestinian Gaza Strip|date=March 22, 2019|access-date=March 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322220129/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-corona-palestinians-gaza/first-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-the-palestinian-gaza-strip-idUSKBN219004|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/palestinians-announce-first-two-cases-of-coronavirus-in-gaza-strip/|title=Palestinians announce first two cases of coronavirus in Gaza Strip|date=March 21, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020|work=Times of Israel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322140612/https://www.timesofisrael.com/palestinians-announce-first-two-cases-of-coronavirus-in-gaza-strip/|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/latest-on-coronavirus-outbreak/palestinians-confirm-first-coronavirus-cases-in-gaza/1774636|title=Palestinians confirm first coronavirus cases in Gaza|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323182149/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/latest-on-coronavirus-outbreak/palestinians-confirm-first-coronavirus-cases-in-gaza/1774636|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 22 March, a patient in [[Zambia]] had travelled to [[Pakistan]] and had contracted COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://diggers.news/breaking/2020/03/22/zambia-confirms-third-coronavirus-case/|title=Zambia confirms third coronavirus case|date=22 March 2020|newspaper=News Diggers|accessdate=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322164152/https://diggers.news/breaking/2020/03/22/zambia-confirms-third-coronavirus-case/|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, Pakistani squash player [[Azam Khan (squash player)|Azam Khan]] died of COVID-19 in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]], at the age of 95.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.urdupoint.com/en/sports/squash-legendary-azam-khan-dies-of-coronaviru-877132.html|title=Squash Legendary Azam Khan Dies Of Coronavirus Aged 95|website=UrduPoint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329091910/https://www.urdupoint.com/en/sports/squash-legendary-azam-khan-dies-of-coronaviru-877132.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Prevention measures and response==\n===Federal government===\n====March 2020====\nThe national carrier, [[Pakistan International Airlines|PIA]] decided to suspend the flight operation between Pakistan and China till January 30 due to the outbreak. After confirmed reports of hundreds of cases in neighbouring [[China]], the [[Pakistan Civil Aviation Authority]] (CAA) introduced screening measures at four major airports: [[Islamabad International Airport|Islamabad]], [[Jinnah International Airport|Karachi]], [[Allama Iqbal International Airport|Lahore]] and [[Bacha Khan International Airport|Peshawar]] for every passenger arriving from China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/pakistan-on-high-alert-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china-1.69234333|title=Pakistan on high alert amid coronavirus outbreak in China|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126044517/https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/pakistan-on-high-alert-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china-1.69234333|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Screening was also started for domestic travellers at Karachi's airport on 21 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/pakistan/2020/03/karachi-airport-starts-coronavirus-screening-of-domestic-travellers/|title=Karachi airport starts coronavirus screening of domestic travellers|website=samaa.tv|date=21 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322114820/https://www.samaa.tv/news/pakistan/2020/03/karachi-airport-starts-coronavirus-screening-of-domestic-travellers/|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, President [[Arif Alvi|Dr. Arif Alvi]] in a special tweet, advised the public to avoid participation in mass gatherings, handshaking or hugging in addition to taking other precautionary measures if they observe symptoms of flu or coronavirus infection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawnnews.tv/news/1122234/|title=First locally transmitted case of coronavirus|website=www.dawnnews.tv|date=13 March 2020|language=Urdu|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314135121/https://www.dawnnews.tv/news/1122234/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ArifAlvi/status/1238288917658587138?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1238288917658587138&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dawnnews.tv%2Fnews%2F1122234 |title= Tweet|website=www.twitter.com/ArifAlvi|language=Urdu|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Pakistan also stopped all international flights, except those at [[Islamabad International Airport|Islamabad]], [[Jinnah International Airport|Karachi]] and [[Allama Iqbal International Airport|Lahore]] airports on the day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samaa.tv/living/health/2020/03/number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-pakistan-jumps-to-28-officials/|title=Number of coronavirus cases in Pakistan jumps to 28: officials {{!}} SAMAA|website=Samaa TV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313234050/https://www.samaa.tv/living/health/2020/03/number-of-coronavirus-cases-in-pakistan-jumps-to-28-officials/|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIt was also decided on 13 March at the [[National Security Council (Pakistan)|National Security Council meeting]] with Prime Minister [[Imran Khan]] that all schools and universities would be closed until 5 April. However, the faculty and staff will go to work as usual. The lectures and classes will be held online in some institutions i.e., Riphah International University, FAST NUCES University, Institute of Space Technology.<ref name=\"Border and school closures\"/><ref name=\"school closures\">{{Cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/575542/schools-colleges-and-universities-in-pakistan-to-remain-closed-till-april-5-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Schools, colleges and universities in Pakistan to remain closed till April 5 amid coronavirus outbreak|website=www.dailytimes.com|date=2020-03-13|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322184837/https://dailytimes.com.pk/575542/schools-colleges-and-universities-in-pakistan-to-remain-closed-till-april-5-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Pakistan Day|Pakistan Day Parade]], scheduled to be held on 23 March was also cancelled along with all public events<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/277199-government-decides-to-cancel-pakistan-day-parade-amid-coronavirus-fears|title=Pakistan Day Parade cancelled amid coronavirus fears|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133721/https://www.geo.tv/latest/277199-government-decides-to-cancel-pakistan-day-parade-amid-coronavirus-fears|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and proceedings of the [[Senate of Pakistan|Senate]] were postponed for two weeks on the day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/pakistan-closes-schools-universities-over-coronavirus/1765276|title=Pakistan closes schools, universities over coronavirus|website=www.aa.com|language=en-US|date=2020-03-13|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323133550/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/pakistan-closes-schools-universities-over-coronavirus/1765276|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPakistan closed its borders to travellers from [[Afghanistan]] at the [[Wesh\u2013Chaman border crossing|Chaman border]] from 2 until 21 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/278438-pakistan-opens-border-with-afghanistan-despite-coronavirus-fears|title=Pakistan opens border with Afghanistan to allow essential goods to pass through|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321100345/https://www.geo.tv/latest/278438-pakistan-opens-border-with-afghanistan-despite-coronavirus-fears|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The border was only partially reopened later after 21 March for transportation of food items while pedestrian movement remained suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radio.gov.pk/21-03-2020/pak-afghan-border-opened-for-transportation-of-food-items|title=Pak-Afghan border at Chaman opened for transportation of essential food items|website=www.radio.gov.pk|language=en-US|date=21 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323095354/https://www.radio.gov.pk/21-03-2020/pak-afghan-border-opened-for-transportation-of-food-items|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Durand Line|Durand Line border]] was sealed from 16 March for at least two weeks. The same time period also applied to [[Taftan, Balochistan|the land border with Iran]] after reopening it on 7 March from a previous closure.<ref name=\"Border and school closures\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/277163-pakistan-set-to-seal-border-with-afghanistan-iran-to-prevent-coronavirus-spread|title=Pakistan set to seal border with Afghanistan, Iran to prevent coronavirus spread|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134353/https://www.geo.tv/latest/277163-pakistan-set-to-seal-border-with-afghanistan-iran-to-prevent-coronavirus-spread|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/23/turkey-and-pakistan-close-borders-with-iran-over-coronavirus-deaths|title=Turkey and Pakistan close borders with Iran over coronavirus deaths {{!}} Coronavirus outbreak {{!}} The Guardian|website=amp.theguardian.com|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/535901-Coronavirus-Pak-Afghan-border-remain-closed-another-week|title=Coronavirus: Pak-Afghan border to remain closed for another week|website=Dunya News|access-date=2020-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320093508/https://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/535901-Coronavirus-Pak-Afghan-border-remain-closed-another-week|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/625285-coronavirus-after-14-days-pakistan-opens-taftan-border-with-iran-for-trade|title=Coronavirus: After 14 days, Pakistan opens Taftan border with Iran for trade|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312042316/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/625285-coronavirus-after-14-days-pakistan-opens-taftan-border-with-iran-for-trade|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> All land borders, including the [[China\u2013Pakistan border|China-Pakistan border]] with [[China]] were shut from 16 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://skift.com/2020/03/13/pakistan-shuts-borders-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Pakistan Shuts Borders Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|date=2020-03-13|website=Skift|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317161936/https://skift.com/2020/03/13/pakistan-shuts-borders-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLieutenant General Muhammad Afzal, the [[National Disaster Management Authority (Pakistan)|NDMA]] chairman, announced that the government was working on securing more PPEs and other resources for healthcare workers on 20 March.<ref name=\"doctors complain\"/>\n\nOn 21 March, all international flights were suspended for two weeks. The Civil Aviation Authority stated, \"[The] government of Pakistan has decided to suspend operation of all international passenger, chartered and private flights to Pakistan, effective from March 21 till April 4\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/21/pakistan-suspends-international-flights-for-two-weeks-to-stem-covid-19-spread|title=Pakistan suspends international flights for two weeks|website=www.theguardian.com|date=21 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322114816/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/21/pakistan-suspends-international-flights-for-two-weeks-to-stem-covid-19-spread|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-pakistan-suspends-international-flights-operations-for-2-weeks|title=Coronavirus: Pakistan suspends international flights for 2 weeks|website=www.khaleejtimes.in|date=21 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322114818/https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-pakistan-suspends-international-flights-operations-for-2-weeks|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This led to many citizens being stranded in the [[Middle East]], [[Thailand]] and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arynews.tv/en/pakistan-doha-expats/|title=Pakistan gets clearance for expats stranded in Doha, will return tonight|website=www.arynews.tv|date=23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324095442/https://arynews.tv/en/pakistan-doha-expats/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Railways Minister [[Sheikh Rasheed Ahmed]] declared the suspension of 42 trains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radio.gov.pk/21-03-2020/railways-minister-announces-to-suspend-42-trains|title=Railways Minister announces to suspend 42 trains|website=www.radio.gov.pk|date=21 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323095353/https://www.radio.gov.pk/21-03-2020/railways-minister-announces-to-suspend-42-trains|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ministry of National Health Services, Regulation and Coordination|health ministry]] announced that 14 metric tonnes of PPE, \"including face masks, thermometers, gloves [and] gowns\", had been dispatched to Pakistan on 22 March.<ref name=\"doctors complain\"/> The federal government offered financial assistance to Sindh by allotting the province $10 million from the non-development funds of the [[World Bank]] the same day. [[Imran Ismail]], the Governor of Sindh stated that the federal government was taking \"vigorous measures\" to control the outbreak and that rations will be provided to the families of patients.<ref name=\"Sindh response\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1542702/centre-to-give-sindh-govt-10m-from-wb-funds-to-fight-coronavirus|title=Centre to give Sindh govt $10m from WB funds to fight coronavirus|website=www.dawn.com|date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322060631/https://www.dawn.com/news/1542702/centre-to-give-sindh-govt-10m-from-wb-funds-to-fight-coronavirus|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, the nation celebrated [[Pakistan Day]] without any public gatherings or military parade. The Prime Minister Imran Khan and President Dr. Arif Alvi urged the nation to demonstrate unity, discipline and passion in fighting the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/278714-president-alvi-pm-imran-urge-unity-as-nation-marks-pakistan-day-with-pledge-to-fight-coronavirus|title=President Alvi, PM Imran urge unity as nation marks Pakistan Day with pledge to fight coronavirus|website=www.geo.tv|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323081421/https://www.geo.tv/latest/278714-president-alvi-pm-imran-urge-unity-as-nation-marks-pakistan-day-with-pledge-to-fight-coronavirus|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The PM also stated that a complete lockdown of the country was not feasible as 25% of the population lives below the poverty line and would make their lives miserable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radio.gov.pk/22-03-2020/pm-to-address-nation-on-challenges-posed-by-coronavirus|title=PM appeals nation to observe self-discipline and quarantine to fight Coronavirus pandemic|website=www.radio.gov.pk|date=22 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322192853/https://www.radio.gov.pk/22-03-2020/pm-to-address-nation-on-challenges-posed-by-coronavirus|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The government has over 35 hospitals across the country set up to deal with the outbreak, equipped with more than 118,000 beds as of the day.<ref name=\"doctors complain\"/>\n\nThe [[National Assembly of Pakistan|National Assembly]] speaker [[Asad Qaiser]] summoned a meeting of the parliamentary leaders of the Senate and the [[National Assembly of Pakistan|Lower house]] to review and discuss the role of the [[Parliament of Pakistan|Parliament]] in containing the spread of the pandemic across the country for 25 March on the day.<ref name=\"NA meeting\">{{Cite web|url=https://arynews.tv/en/na-speaker-asad-qaiser-parliamentary-leaders-meeting-coronavirus/|title=Asad Qaiser summons meeting of NA, Senate parliamentary leaders|website=www.arynews.tv|date=23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323133550/https://arynews.tv/en/na-speaker-asad-qaiser-parliamentary-leaders-meeting-coronavirus/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the Chief of the Army Staff General [[Qamar Javed Bajwa]] ordered the deployment of troops nationwide and military's medical resources to fight the ongoing outbreak alongside the national health infrastructure after the Ministry of Interior approved the action on the previous day. The Ministry had received requests in this regard from the provincial governments over the past two days amid surging number of patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1543293/troops-deployed-to-fight-virus|title=Troops deployed to fight virus|website=www.dawn.com|date=24 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324095441/https://www.dawn.com/news/1543293/troops-deployed-to-fight-virus|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/pakistan-deploys-army-to-assist-in-covid-19-measures/1776226|title=Pakistan deploys army to assist in COVID-19 measures|website=www.aa.tr|date=23 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324180955/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/pakistan-deploys-army-to-assist-in-covid-19-measures/1776226|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[State Bank of Pakistan]] issued a statement the same day declaring that it would be providing disinfected cash to all banks for circulation while ensuring to \"clean, disinfect, seal and quarantine all cash being collected from hospitals and clinics and to block circulation of such cash in the market.\" It was further assured that banks could re-issue cash which remained in quarantine for 15 days and all ATMs as well as call centres and helplines would be running 24/7. Banks could close branches only if a staff member tested positive for the virus or \"where requisite human resources [were] not available\" to avoid congestion as it would be counterproductive to [[social distancing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2182617/1-sbp-ensure-provision-disinfected-cash-availability-atms-amid-virus-crisis/|title=SBP to ensure provision of 'disinfected cash', availability of ATMs amid virus crisis|website=www.tribune.com.pk|date=24 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The federal capital territory of Islamabad was placed under virtual lockdown starting on 24 March.<ref>[https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/634351-islamabad-placed-under-virtual-lockdown-to-curb-spread-of-coronavirus Islamabad placed under virtual lockdown to curb spread of coronavirus], The News, March 25, 2020</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, Pakistan decided to seek $3.7 billion additional financing from three multilateral creditors including another loan of $1.4 billion from the [[International Monetary Fund]] to cope with the challenges being posed by the novel coronavirus outbreak. Adviser to the PM on Finance Dr [[Abdul Hafeez Shaikh]] announced at a news conference that the [[World Bank]] and the [[Asian Development Bank]] would also extend loans of $1 billion and $1.25 billion respectively to the country.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe PM announced formation of youth force labelled \u2018Corona Relief Tigers\u2019 to help government in fight against the spread of coronavirus nationwide on 27 March. The force was distributed across the country and would be used to supply food items to people in their houses in case Covid-19 cases sharply rose in a locality. The recruitment began on 31 March.<ref>[http://www.aaj.tv/english/national/pm-announces-formation-of-corona-relief-tigers-to-fight-virus/ PM announces formation of \u2018corona relief tigers\u2019 to fight virus], Aaj News, March 27, 2020</ref>\n\nDue to various lockdowns imposed by the regional governments, the goods transport system came to a halt in later March. Thus, the federal government decided on 29 March that highways and roads across the country would remain open to ensure the transportation of goods and also increased the number of freight trains to avert a shortage of food and other essential supplies. Chairing a meeting, the Prime Minister asked the provincial governments to take strict action against hoarders and profiteers who were trying to exploit the ongoing crisis.<ref name=\"martyrs\">[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2187077/1-centre-decides-open-roads-across-country/ Centre decides to open roads across country], The Express Tribune, March 30, 2020</ref> By late March, many regions in Pakistan had considered releasing under-trial prisoners to curb the outbreak in jails. However, on 30 March, the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan|Supreme Court]] refrained high courts and federal and provincial governments to pass any order regarding the release of under-trial prisoners.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2187264/1-covid-19-sc-refrains-high-courts-federal-provincial-govts-releasing-utps/ COVID-19: SC refrains high courts, federal and provincial govts from releasing UTPs], The Express Tribiune, 30 March 2020</ref>\n\nAlso on 30 March, the State Minister for Health, Dr [[Zafar Mirza]] announced that the Higher Education Commission (HEC) was inviting proposals from researchers, scientists, technicians, manufacturers and other experts that could assist the government in its fight against Covid-19, adding that the commission would provide generous funding to prospective researchers if their ideas are accepted. Meanwhile, the Lt. Gen. Afzal said that Sindh had been provided 20,000 testing kits, Punjab 5,000, Balochistan 4,800 and that up to 37,000 kits had been put into reserve.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2187677/1-new-infections-fall-patients-recover/ New infections fall as more patients recover], The Express Tribune, 31 March 2020</ref> The Federal Minister for Inter Provincial Coordination Dr. [[Fehmida Mirza]] announced to create a fund to cover all medical expenses of sports persons infected with COVID-19 on that day.<ref name=\"sports fund\" />\n\n====April 2020====\nOn 1 April, Special Assistant on Information and Broadcasting Dr. [[Firdous Ashiq Awan]] said that protective kits would be provided to the journalists covering vulnerable areas including quarantine centers. She also announced the launching of an app called COVID-19 Care for Media to help the journalists affected by the virus. Furthermore, newspapers hawkers would also be registered in Ehsaas Emergency Cash program; part of the economic relief package announced by the federal government, as their sales had also been affected due to the outbreak.<ref>[https://www.radio.gov.pk/01-04-2020/protective-kits-will-be-provided-to-journalists-covering-vulnerable-areas-firdous Protective kits will be provided to journalists covering vulnerable areas: Firdous] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401235546/http://www.radio.gov.pk/01-04-2020/protective-kits-will-be-provided-to-journalists-covering-vulnerable-areas-firdous |date=1 April 2020 }}, Radio Pakistan, 1 April 2020</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, the Federal Minister for Planning and Development [[Asad Umar]] announced that the country was extending the ongoing lockdown for another two weeks until 14 April to curb the spread of the pandemic in the country.<ref name=\"lockdowns2\">[https://www.thestatesman.com/world/coronavirus-pandemic-pakistan-extend-lockdown-2-weeks-death-toll-reaches-31-1502872742.html Coronavirus pandemic: Pakistan to extend lockdown for 2 more weeks as death toll reaches 31] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408000401/https://www.thestatesman.com/world/coronavirus-pandemic-pakistan-extend-lockdown-2-weeks-death-toll-reaches-31-1502872742.html |date=8 April 2020 }}, The Statesman, 2 April 2020</ref> On 14 April, the Prime Minister announced that the ongoing lockdown would be extended for two more weeks until 30 April.<ref name=\"lockdowns3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-pakistan-extends-lockdown-until-april-30/1804544|title=COVID-19: Pakistan extends lockdown until April 30|work=Anadolu Agency|date=14 April 2020|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> On 24 April, the federal government once again extended the lockdown in the country until 9 May.<ref name=\"lockdowns4\"/>\n\n====Economic Relief Package====\nOn 24 March, the Prime Minister approved a Rs1.2 trillion economic relief package. Of this, a total of Rs150 billion was allotted for low-income groups, particularly laborers while 280 billion rupees ($1.76 billion) was assigned for wheat procurement. Loan interest payments for exporters were deferred temporarily, while a package of 100 billion rupees ($63 million) was provided to support small industries and the agriculture sector. There was also a significant deduction in petroleum prices and the public couple pay electricity and gas bills below a certain amount in installments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/25-Mar-2020/pm-announces-record-economic-relief-package|title=M announces record economic relief package|website=www.nation.com.pk|date=25 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328182553/https://nation.com.pk/25-Mar-2020/pm-announces-record-economic-relief-package|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-pakistan-unveils-economic-relief-package/1777961|title=COVID-19: Pakistan unveils economic relief package|website=www.aa.com.tr|date=24 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325105033/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19-pakistan-unveils-economic-relief-package/1777961|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Under the package the monthly stipend of the [[Benazir Income Support Programme]] (BISP) was increased from Rs2,000 to Rs3,000. It was decided that the funds of the government's Ehsaas programme would be distributed among the poor according to the available data of the BISP and through the under progress National Socio-Economic Registry (NSER) of the BISP. The total number of BISP beneficiaries was 5.2 million but the number was increased under the package.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1543282/multi-billion-rupee-relief-package-approved|title=Multi-billion rupee relief package approved|website=www.dawn.com|date=24 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324095439/https://www.dawn.com/news/1543282/multi-billion-rupee-relief-package-approved|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The relief package also included a special package for healthcare professionals. According to which, if a doctor or a paramedic died while treating coronavirus patients, they would be considered martyrs and their families would receive the package that is given to martyrs.<ref name=\"martyrs\"/>\n\nThe federal cabinet reviewed and approved the economic relief package on 31 March. The [[Economic Coordination Committee (Pakistan)|Economic Coordination Committee]] (ECC) finalised the package, including a Rs100-billion supplementary grant for an Emergency Relief Fund to combat the pandemic. It also approved a special package for relief to 12 million poor families through cash assistance under the Ehsaas Programme, where cash grants would be provided under the Kafalat Programme and emergency cash assistance to the poor on the recommendation of the district administration. The financial assistance was provided for four months as a one-time dispensation. The cash would be provided either in one Rs12,000 installment through Kafalat partner banks, [[Bank Alfalah]] and [[Habib Bank Limited]] after biometric verification or in two installments of Rs6,000 each.<ref>[https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/637393-federal-cabinet-discusses-economy-approves-coronavirus-relief-package Coronavirus relief fund approved by federal cabinet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401000325/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/637393-federal-cabinet-discusses-economy-approves-coronavirus-relief-package |date=1 April 2020 }}, The News, 31 March 2020</ref> Since its launch, a total of Rs22.466 billion has been disbursed among 1.77 million individuals as of mid April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2196508/1-rs22-466-billion-disbursed-ehsaas-emergency-programme-says-pms-aide/|title=Rs22.466 billion disbursed under Ehsaas Emergency Programme: Dr Sania Nishtar|website=www.tribune.com.pk|date=12 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Regional governments===\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Current lockdown regions{{efn|As of 14 April 2020}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"1\" | Province or Territory\n! colspan=\"1\" | Start Date\n! colspan=\"1\" | End Date\n|-\n|-\n| Punjab<ref name=\"punjab lockdown\"/>\n! rowspan=\"5\" |24 March\n! rowspan=\"7\" |30 April<ref name=\"lockdowns3\"/> \n|-\n| Sindh<ref name=\"sindh lockdown\"/>\n|-\n| Azad Kashmir<ref name=\"ajk lockdown\"/>\n|-\n| Balochistan<ref name=\"balochistan lockdown\"/>\n|-\n| Islamabad{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n|-\n| Khyber Pakhtunkhwa<ref name=\"kp lockdown\"/>\n! 23 March\n|-\n| Gilgit-Baltistan<ref name=\"gb lockdown\"/>\n! 22 March\n|-\n|}\n\n====Punjab====\nThe [[Government of Punjab, Pakistan|Government]] of Punjab declared a health emergency on 12 March in a cabinet meeting. A quarantine facility was established in the [[Dera Ghazi Khan]] district for the pilgrims returning from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]].<ref name=\"school closures\"/>\n\nOn 22 March, the government decided to close down shopping malls, markets, parks and public gathering places for two days till 24 March. Punjab Chief Minister, [[Sardar Usman Buzdar]] urged people to stay at home, practice [[social distancing]] and avoid unnecessary travel.<ref>{{cite news |title=Punjab Govt decides to close malls, markets, parks till Tuesday |url=https://www.radio.gov.pk/22-03-2020/punjab-govt-decides-to-close-malls-markets-parks-till-tuesday |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Radio Pakistan |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322192847/https://www.radio.gov.pk/22-03-2020/punjab-govt-decides-to-close-malls-markets-parks-till-tuesday |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite this, local media reported that many residents in Lahore had failed to practice the measures and downright defied it by opening up businesses and gathering in large numbers on various public grounds. This led to the local police and city administration to forcibly vacate them.<ref>{{cite news |title=Punjab govt's repeated pleas for social distancing fall on deaf ears |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/278721-punjab-govts-repeated-pleas-for-social-distancing-fall-on-deaf-ears |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Geo News |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323081413/https://www.geo.tv/latest/278721-punjab-govts-repeated-pleas-for-social-distancing-fall-on-deaf-ears |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, The Chief Minister announced a 14 days lockdown from 24 March till 6 April. All markets, shopping malls and public places were closed and [[pillion]] riding was banned.<ref name=\"punjab lockdown\">{{cite news |title=CM Punjab Usman Buzdar announces lockdown in Punjab |url=https://arynews.tv/en/cm-punjab-usman-buzdar-lockdown-punjab/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=ARY News |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323154147/https://arynews.tv/en/cm-punjab-usman-buzdar-lockdown-punjab/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He also stated that a 1,000 bed hospital would be setup in [[Lahore]] while five other hospitals were designated for coronavirus patients across the province the next day on 23 March while the local government and rescue services started disinfecting towns and cities. Public bus services were also temporarily suspended to disinfect all buses and stations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Punjab Local Govt, Rescue 1122 jointly working to disinfect cities, towns |url=https://www.radio.gov.pk/23-03-2020/punjab-local-govt-rescue-1122-jointly-working-to-disinfect-cities-towns |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Radio Pakistan |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323083725/https://www.radio.gov.pk/23-03-2020/punjab-local-govt-rescue-1122-jointly-working-to-disinfect-cities-towns |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Secretary Home Department of Punjab wrote a letter one the day to the [[Ministry of Interior (Pakistan)|Ministry of Interior]] seeking the assistance of the military under Article 245.<ref name=\"NA meeting\"/> The [[University of the Punjab|Punjab University]] manufactured coronavirus protection kits along with large amounts of hand sanitisers, disinfectants and antiseptic wet-tissues for the public. The sanitisers are for national usage. An online initiative was started for online purchases for home deliveries.<ref name=\"university action\">{{cite news |title=JPMC designates ward for coronavirus quarantine, conducting free tests |url=https://arynews.tv/en/jpmc-designates-ward-for-coronavirus/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=ARY News |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323135117/https://arynews.tv/en/jpmc-designates-ward-for-coronavirus/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on the day, more than 150 pilgrims arrived in [[Faisalabad]] from Iran via the Taftan border to be quarantined at a centre. More arrangements were made to quarantine another 450 pilgrims returning at a centre established in the campus of the [[University of Agriculture, Faisalabad|Agricultural University]]. The government established the largest quarantine centre in the nation in [[Multan]] at Multan Industrial Estate to isolate the returning pilgrims with 3000 rooms. It had 1,247 pilgrims in quarantine as of the day. A companion 50 bed hospital was also setup to aid the centre.<ref>{{cite news |title=More than 150 pilgrims from Taftan reach Faisalabad |url=https://arynews.tv/en/more-than-150-pilgrims-from-taftan-reach-faisalabad/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=ARY News |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323133556/https://arynews.tv/en/more-than-150-pilgrims-from-taftan-reach-faisalabad/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe provincial government decided to close down the regional motorways except for private vehicles with up to two passengers as a preventive measure on 26 March.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2185013/1-motorways-closed-curb-mobility/ Motorways closed to curb mobility],The Express Tribune, 27 March 2020</ref> The NIH initiated district level training of [[high-dependency unit]], isolation and quarantine staff across the province on 27 March.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC7\"/>\n\nThe Chief Minister of the province announced a Rs10 billion relief package for financial support of 2.5 million families of daily-wage earners on 28 March. Each family was entitled to Rs4,000 financial assistance excluding the beneficiaries of the Benazir Income Support Programme (BISP).<ref>[https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/636482-bisp-beneficiaries-not-included-in-punjab-govt-relief-package-awan Punjab govt relief package not for BISP beneficiaries: Awan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330161953/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/636482-bisp-beneficiaries-not-included-in-punjab-govt-relief-package-awan |date=30 March 2020 }}, The News, 29 March 2020</ref><ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2186491/1-fighting-covid-19-punjab-govt-announces-rs10b-relief-package/ Fighting COVID-19: Punjab govt announces Rs10b relief package],The Express Tribune, 29 March 2020</ref> The government also decided to remove provincial taxes to the tune of Rs18bn. The CM said that the Punjab government had decided to grant a 90-day imprisonment rebate to prisoners in jails across the province which would benefit some 3,100 prisoners. Furthermore, the Punjab Infectious Diseases Prevention and Control Ordinance, 2020, was implemented to allow the civil administration and health department to implement government measures with complete ease and under the cover of law. It was also declared that the government would provide a month's additional salary to all healthcare workers across Punjab.<ref name=\"punjab relief\">{{cite news |title=Punjab unveils Rs10bn relief package for daily-wage earners |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1544624/punjab-unveils-rs10bn-relief-package-for-daily-wage-earners |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=Dawn |date=29 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329221653/https://www.dawn.com/news/1544624/punjab-unveils-rs10bn-relief-package-for-daily-wage-earners |archive-date=29 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://www.bolnews.com/pakistan/2020/03/punjab-gov-passes-infectious-disease-prevention-control-ordinance-2020/ Punjab gov passes Infectious Disease Prevention & Control Ordinance 2020], Bol Network, 29 March 2020</ref> The Punjab Minister for Finance Hashim Jawan Bakht said that the economic package would also help the health sector and the Provincial Disaster Management Authority (PDMA) cope with the crisis with an immediate funding of Rs11.5 billion. To aid the medical professionals, a textile owner from Lahore offered to manufacture PPE voluntarily and free of cost.<ref name=\"punjab relief2\">{{cite news |title=Fighting COVID-19: Punjab govt announces Rs10b relief package |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2186491/1-fighting-covid-19-punjab-govt-announces-rs10b-relief-package/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=The Express Tribune |date=29 March 2020}}</ref> Also in the meeting, the CM stated that laboratories around the province would test 3,200 people every day for coronavirus and 10,000 doctors and paramedics were being recruited to fight the pandemic.<ref name=\"martyrs\"/>\n\nThe Chief Minister Insaf Imdaad Programme (CMIIP) was launched on 1 April to help the daily wagers and the poor communities of the province affected by the pandemic. Furthermore, Zakat funds worth Rs870 million were also released to help around 170,000 families. A 1,000-bed [[field hospital]] was completed at the [[Lahore Expo Centre]] and the Punjab government also announced on the day that it had released Rs620 million for the establishment of eight new diagnostic labs at divisional level to speed up the testing process for COVID-19.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2189035/1-fighting-covid-19-rs620m-allocated-new-diagnostic-labs/ Fighting COVID-19: Rs620m allocated for new diagnostic labs], The Express Tribune, 2 April 2020</ref> Starting from 2 April, the lockdown in the province was extended until 14 April as per directions by the federal government.<ref name=\"lockdowns2\"/> On 14 April, the lockdown period was further extended for two weeks, until 30 April by the federal government.<ref name=\"lockdowns3\"/> The same day, Lahore police reported that a total of 13,498 cases had been registered against lockdown violators since 16 March.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2197420/1-police-register-13498-cases-lockdown-violation/ Police register 13,498 cases over lockdown violation], The Express Tribune, 14 April 2020</ref>\n\nBy early April, the province suspended regular prayer services in places of worship to stop the spread of COVID-19.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2192361/1-religious-groups-forced-stay-away-places-worship/ Religious groups forced to stay away from places of worship], The Express Tribune, 8 April 2020</ref> Punjab Chief Secretary, [[Azam Suleman Khan]] relayed to media on 6 April that field hospitals for coronavirus patients were being established across the province and two of these would be functional in [[Rawalpindi]] and [[Jhelum]] in the next three days.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2191678/1-field-hospitals-ready-fight-coronavirus-lahore-city/ \u2018Field hospitals ready to fight coronavirus\u2019], The Express Tribune, 6 April 2020</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, the Lahore District Jail Superintendent urged authorities to not send any new inmates to the prison after 49 positive cases emerged there in addition to over 150 suspects.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2193046/1-district-jail-declines-accept-new-prisoners/ District jail declines to accept new prisoners], The Express Tribune, 8 April 2020</ref> On 10 April, the Punjab Minister for Law, Parliamentary Affairs and Social Welfare [[Muhammad Basharat Raja]] stated that a transfer plan had been made to shift 3,500 prisoners from overcrowded jails to others to curb the spread of coronavirus in prisons of the province.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2195423/1-3500-prisoners-shifted-overcrowded-jails/ \u20183,500 prisoners to be shifted from overcrowded jails\u2019], The Express Tribune, 11 April 2020</ref> Also on the day, the provincial Information Minister, [[Fayyazul Hassan Chohan]] declared a relief package for media workers and personnel. Under the package, the government would pay Rs1 million to any journalist who died due to COVID-19 while his widow would get Rs10,000 as monthly pension for life. Rs100,000 would also be provided to any media worker diagnosed with the coronavirus.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2195212/1-punjab-govt-announces-relief-package-media-workers-amid-pandemic/ Punjab govt announces relief package for media workers amid pandemic], The Express Tribune, 10 April 2020</ref>\n\nAt least 1,700 pilgrims returning from Iran were quarantined at a centre in [[Multan]] on April 16.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2191657/1-multan-quarantine-centre-host-1700-pilgrims/ Multan quarantine centre to host 1,700 more pilgrims], The Express Tribune, 6 April 2020</ref>\n\n==== Sindh ====\n[[File:Covid-19-curves-graphic-social-v3-sd.gif|thumb|300px|left|\"Flatten the curve\" campaign in [[Sindhi (language)|Sindhi]] on social distancing .]]\n\nOn 1 March, [[Chief Minister of Sindh]], [[Syed Murad Ali Shah]], announced the closure of all educational institutes in Sindh until 13 March,<ref>{{cite news |title=Schools to remain closed in Sindh till March 13 |url=https://nation.com.pk/01-Mar-2020/schools-to-remain-closed-in-si |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Nation |date=1 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304123506/https://nation.com.pk/01-Mar-2020/schools-to-remain-closed-in-si |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2167367/1-coronavirus-threat-educational-institutions-sindh-remain-shut-till-march-13/|title=Sindh extends closure of all educational institutions till March 13 amid virus fear|last=|first=|date=March 2020|website=Tribune.com.pk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which was later extended until 30 May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/628126-govt-extends-educational-institutions-holidays-till-may-30-amid-coronavirus-fears|title=Sindh govt extends closure of educational institutions till May 30 amid coronavirus fears|website=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313125047/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/628126-govt-extends-educational-institutions-holidays-till-may-30-amid-coronavirus-fears|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 March, [[Government of Sindh|the Government of Sindh]] also announced that the remaining [[2020 Pakistan Super League|PSL matches]] at [[National Stadium, Karachi|National Stadium]], [[Karachi]] would be held [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/276984-coronavirus-psl-2020-matches-in-karachi-to-take-place-without-crowd-says-murtaza-wahab|title=Coronavirus: PSL 2020 matches in Karachi to take place without crowd, says Murtaza Wahab|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> The Sindh government announced on 13 March that all educational institutions will remain closed until 30 May<ref name=\"school closures\"/> imposed a temporary ban on marriage halls, shrines and festivals in the province on 14 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Sindh govt closes wedding halls, shrines across province |url=https://arynews.tv/en/wedding-halls-shrines-closed-in-sindh/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=ARY NEWS |date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322133804/https://arynews.tv/en/wedding-halls-shrines-closed-in-sindh/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, the [[Pakistan Army]] helped setup a 10,000-bed field hospital at Karachi's [[Karachi Expo Center|Expo Centre]] to isolate and treat confirmed patients. ALl expenses for its establishment were born by the provincial government.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Pakistan Army helps set up field hospital at Karachi's Expo Centre |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/631969-coronavirus-pakistan-army-helps-set-up-field-hospital-at-karachis-expo-centre |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The News |date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321170828/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/631969-coronavirus-pakistan-army-helps-set-up-field-hospital-at-karachis-expo-centre |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 21 March, the Government of Sindh announced a lockdown in the province for 14 days from morning of 24 March, ordering all public transport, markets, offices, shopping malls, restaurants, and public areas to be shut down.<ref name=\"sindh lockdown\">{{cite news |title=Sindh decides to go into COVID-19 lock down |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2181138/1-sindh-govt-mulls-total-lockdown-provincial-covid-19-tally-crosses-350/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Express Tribune |date=21 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324215630/https://tribune.com.pk/story/2181138/1-sindh-govt-mulls-total-lockdown-provincial-covid-19-tally-crosses-350/ |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"lockdowns\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Pakistan reports 4th death due to COVID-19 on Sunday as the country heads towards lockdown |url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/coronavirus-pakistan-reports-4th-death-due-to-covid-19-on-sunday-as-the-country-heads-towards-lockdown-1.70552122 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Gulf News |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322131617/https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/pakistan/coronavirus-pakistan-reports-4th-death-due-to-covid-19-on-sunday-as-the-country-heads-towards-lockdown-1.70552122 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Sindh government announced paid leave for all workers during the lockdown, and said no would be laid off during the period under Section 3 of the Sindh Epidemic Diseases Act (2014) and other relevant labor laws.<ref>[https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/633533-sindh-govt-bars-employers-from-laying-off-workers-during-lockdown-period Sindh govt bars employers from laying off workers during lockdown period] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205544/https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/633533-sindh-govt-bars-employers-from-laying-off-workers-during-lockdown-period |date=25 March 2020 }}, The News, 24 March 2020</ref> The province banned intra-city transport to minimize the outbreak and multiple violators were issued fines, impounded and canceled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sindh observing lockdown in effort to prevent spread of Coronavirus |url=https://www.radio.gov.pk/23-03-2020/sindh-observing-lockdown-in-effort-to-prevent-spread-of-coronavirus |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Radio Pakistan |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323083728/https://www.radio.gov.pk/23-03-2020/sindh-observing-lockdown-in-effort-to-prevent-spread-of-coronavirus |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nThe [[Pakistan army|national army]] was called to enfore the lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |title=Intra-city public transport is banned in Sindh: Awais Shah |url=https://arynews.tv/en/intra-city-public-transport-banned-sindh-awais-shah/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=ARY News |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323135116/https://arynews.tv/en/intra-city-public-transport-banned-sindh-awais-shah/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 23 March, an isolation and quarantine centre was completed at the [[Jinnah Postgraduate Medical College]] in Karachi which also provided free tests of suspected cases with results in 8 hours of sample submission.<ref name=\"university action\"/>\n\nThe [[Pakistan Cricket Board]], on request from the Sindh Government, agreed to convert its Hanif Mohammad High Performance Centre into a temporary living area for paramedic staff working at the makeshift hospital at Expo Centre, Karachi on 24 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=PCB converts Karachi High Performance Centre into sanctuary for paramedics |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/581559/pcb-converts-karachi-high-performance-centre-into-sanctuary-for-paramedics/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Daily Times |date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324103838/https://dailytimes.com.pk/581559/pcb-converts-karachi-high-performance-centre-into-sanctuary-for-paramedics/ |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The local police detained 472 people in various districts of the province on the day, with 222 of them in Karachi alone and a total of [[First information report|FIR]]s were registered. The cases pertained to hoarding and profiteering of safety masks and hand sanitisers, large gatherings, opening shops and restaurants and travelling in passenger buses. Multiple violations of the lockdown were observed in several places across the province such as gatherings on the beach, residents being out and major markets, shopping centres, [[bazaar]]s and restaurants remained open.<ref name=\"lockdown arrests\">{{cite news |title=Over 450 held across Sindh on first day of lockdown |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1543279/over-450-held-across-sindh-on-first-day-of-lockdown |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Dawn |date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324171611/https://www.dawn.com/news/1543279/over-450-held-across-sindh-on-first-day-of-lockdown |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As a result, a taskforce meeting led by the Chief Minister was held on the next day on 25 March to take more stringent measures to ensure that all residents abided by the government orders of. It was resolved that all grocery stores and shops apart from pharmacies and medical stores to remain closed between 8pm and 8am. The Sindh Inspector General of Police, Javed Ahmed Mahar was directed to make measures taken in connection with the lockdown and make certain that people were not allowed to roam freely in the city unnecessarily. Additionally, the Chief Secretary and Karachi Commissioner were ordered to ensure that big factories remained closed during the lockdown and direct banks to keep only important branches operational.<ref>{{cite news |title=Toughening lockdown: Sindh govt takes stricter measures |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2183525/1-toughening-lockdown-sindh-govt-takes-stricter-measures/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The Express Tribune |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the provincial health department officials began coronavirus case mapping as per directives by the Chief Minister. He further tasked them with sharing the data with deputy commissioners so necessary measures could be taken to contain the outbreak in their respective areas. Orders were also given to improve sampling arrangements, upon which 18 vehicles of the Indus Hospital were dedicated for collecting samples from homes. The health officials briefed the Chief Minister about a new machine made at at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] in China, which could test secretions from the nose instead of testing throat secretion as was the current procedure. \nAt this, the CM directed the provincial Chief Secretary to consult with medical experts whether procuring the machine would be feasible and if they deemed it to be beneficial, place an order for 100 machines. The CM further stated that he would request the federal government for a special aircraft to transport the machines if the government decided to procure them.<ref name=\"pilgrims return\"/>\n\nOn the same day, the local government also arranged to launch a mobile service across the province to provide rations to the needy along with daily wages to those affected by the pandemic. A number was dedicated for the service and those in need could text there. Moreover, a warehouse was established for storage of ration bags and a helpline set up for people to register for acquiring the bags. The CM also ordered to release Rs341 million for carrying out administrative work under district administrations and spending on facilities provided to pilgrims.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sindh govt to launch mobile service for ration distribution |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2183520/1-sindh-govt-launch-mobile-service-ration-distribution/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The Express Tribune |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Shortly afterward, reports emerged that rations were being denied to minority [[Hinduism in Pakistan|Hindus]] and [[Christians in Pakistan|Christians]] in the coastal areas of Karachi. The [[Saylani Welfare Trust]], carrying out the relief work, said that the aid was reserved for Muslims alone.<ref>[https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-hindus-denied-food-supplies-in-pakistan-s-karachi-120033000041_1.html COVID-19: Hindus denied food supplies in Pakistan's Karachi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403212904/https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-hindus-denied-food-supplies-in-pakistan-s-karachi-120033000041_1.html |date=3 April 2020 }}, Business Standard, 30 March 2020.</ref><ref>\nShafique Khokhar, [http://asianews.it/news-en/Coronavirus:-Karachi-NGO-denies-food-to-poor-Hindus-and-Christians-49699.html Coronavirus: Karachi NGO denies food to poor Hindus and Christians], Asia News (Italy), 30 March 2020.\n</ref> On 14 April, the [[US Commission on International Religious Freedom]] expressed concern with the discrimination. Other organisations, including [[Edhi Foundation]], [[JDC Welfare Organization]] and [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]] are reported to have stepped forward to provide relief to the minorities.<ref>\n[https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/uscirf-says-troubled-by-denial-of-food-to-pakistani-hindus-christians/story-E4XHUc6GOs2TfURkTelnFK.html USCIRF says \u2018troubled\u2019 by denial of food to Pakistani Hindus, Christians amid Covid-19 crisis], Hindustan Times, 14 April 2020.\n</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, public holidays were extended till 5 April in the province while markets and shopping malls were to remain closed till 10 April. Ajmal Wazir, the adviser to the CM stated that the government the government had decided on tax exemption to facilitate the business community and protect jobs with Rs17.5 billion reserved for wheat procurement. An amount of Rs8 billion was also approved for district hospitals to enable them by the urgent supplies.<ref>[https://www.24newshd.tv/27-Mar-2020/kp-allows-private-hospitals-to-conduct-coronavirus-tests KP allows private hospitals to conduct coronavirus tests] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327185516/https://www.24newshd.tv/27-Mar-2020/kp-allows-private-hospitals-to-conduct-coronavirus-tests |date=27 March 2020 }}, 24News, March 27, 2020</ref> To further enforce lockdown, the Sindh govt restricted movement between 8AM and 5PM, while all grocery stores were ordered to be closed by 5 PM. These restrictions went into force on 28 March.<ref>[https://www.oyeyeah.com/news/sindh-restricts-movement-between-8-am-5-pm/ Sindh govt. restricts movement between 8am-5pm as coronavirus cases surge to 440], Saman Siddiqui, OyeYeah News, March 27, 2020</ref> Sindh Province also received 500,000 K [[N95 mask]]s from [[China]].<ref name=\"MoNHSRC4\"/> On 29 March, the Sindh CM approved a proposal to release about 4,000 convicts from prison in order to prevent the spread of the novel coronavirus outbreak in the province's jails.<ref>[https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/29/sindh-cm-approves-release-4000-convicts/ Sindh CM approves release of 4,000 convicts] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330143359/https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/29/sindh-cm-approves-release-4000-convicts/ |date=30 March 2020 }}, Pakistan Today, 29 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, the Chief Minister, Syed Murad Ali Shah made public a mobile application, namely the Sindh Relief Initiative, on which welfare organisations could register to work with the provincial government for the distribution of ration among daily-wagers at their doorstep.<ref>[https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/636777-welfare-organisations-can-register-with-govt-via-mobile-app-for-rations-distribution Welfare organisations can register with govt via mobile app for rations distribution] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331154354/https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/636777-welfare-organisations-can-register-with-govt-via-mobile-app-for-rations-distribution |date=31 March 2020 }}, The News, 30 March 2020</ref> Also on the day, the Mayor of Karachi, [[Wasim Akhtar]] designated five cemeteries in the city for burials of those who died due to coronavirus. He said that only a few close relatives of the deceased could enter the cemetery for burial, adding that the body would be brought into the cemetery with protective measures and no last sighting would be allowed. The mayor also wrote to the National Disaster Management Authority, the provincial government and the Governor [[Imran Ismail]] requesting funds to provide essential equipment and ventilators to Karachi Metropolitan Corporation hospitals.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2187564/1-five-graveyards-designated-coronavirus-victims-karachi/ Five graveyards designated for coronavirus victims in Karachi], The Express Tribune, 30 March 2020</ref> The Sindh government issued a circular directing private schools across the province to pay full salaries to its teachers on time the same day. Another directive was also declared for factories and other private entities operating in the province to disburse salaries to their employees by 31 March.<ref>[https://thepakistanpost.net/sindh-govt-directs-private-schools-to-pay-full-salaries-to-teachers/ Sindh govt directs private schools to pay full salaries to teachers], The Pakistan Post, 30 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, the Sindh government extended the lockdown until April 14. It also announced new restrictions, closing down shrines and other holy sites while suspending inter and intra-city public transport. There was also a restriction on from movement of people from 5:00pm to 08:00am except for armed forces personnel, doctors and health professionals, persons requiring immediate medical care and persons on goods transport.<ref name=\"sindh lockdown2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/280651-coronavirus-sindh-government-issues-new-directives-for-lockdown|title=Coronavirus: Sindh government issues notification extending lockdown till April 14|website=www.geo.tv|access-date=3 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404003653/https://www.geo.tv/latest/280651-coronavirus-sindh-government-issues-new-directives-for-lockdown|archive-date=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"lockdowns2\"/> The local government purchased 50,000 testing kits for the province in early April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arynews.tv/en/sindh-covid-19-testing-kits-karachi/|title=Sindh set to ramp up Covid-19 testing as 50,000 kits reach Karachi|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Balochistan====\nThe [[Government of Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan Government]] constituted a 14-member technical committee in late January to tackle the outbreak.<ref name=\"early measures\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1530743|title=Coronavirus fear: GB seeks delay in opening of border crossing|last=Nagri|first=Ikram Junaidi {{!}} Jamil|date=2020-01-27|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> All schools have been closed till 31 March. Balochistan Minister Sardar Yar Mohammad Rind stated that \"action will be taken against schools that do not comply with the decision\". Matric exams have also been postponed.<ref name=\"school closures\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Balochistan, Sindh education institutes to reopen in March as coronavirus cases confirmed |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/274487-balochistan-shuts-down-schools-till-march-15-after-two-coronavirus-cases-confirmed |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Geo News |date=27 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227210155/https://www.geo.tv/latest/274487-balochistan-shuts-down-schools-till-march-15-after-two-coronavirus-cases-confirmed |archive-date=27 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The province like others also requested for the army to be deployed.<ref name=\"lockdowns\"/>\n\nOn 24 March, the Balochistan government imposed a complete lockdown in the entire province until 7 April. It included a complete ban on public getting out of their homes, all kinds of social and religious gatherings or any public or private event. All public and private offices were ordered closed. Exemptions included essential services such as personnel of hospitals, laboratories and medical stores, law enforcement agencies, people in need of urgent medical care with one attendant, one person per family going out to buy grocery and medicines within the vicinity of their residence and burials of people that had passed away. Only one person was allowed to travel in a private vehicle. Media personnel authorized by concerned media houses and newspaper hawkers were allowed to move freely as well. Public and private telecom companies, essential staff of banks with limited public dealing, defence-related manufacturing industries, food items manufacturing industries and distribution offices, grocery shops, petrol pumps and auto workshops and welfare organizations providing services were given permission to operate. Similar to Gilgit-Baltistan and Islamad, Section 144 was also enforced.<ref name=\"balochistan lockdown\">{{cite news |title=Balochistan goes into lockdown untill April 7 |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2183565/1-balochistan-goes-lockdown-untill-april-7/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The Express Tribune |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> A state of emergency was imposed in five districts which bordered Iran on 24 March.<ref name=\"islamabad measures\"/>\n\n[[Fumigation]] was carried out across the entire central jail of Quetta on 30 March, while spray pumps and disinfectants were distributed to 10 districts of the province.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC8\"/> On 31 March, the provincial government released Rs500 million for upgrading, rehabilitation & establishment of quarantine centres in the areas of [[Quetta]], [[Chaman]], [[Taftan, Balochistan|Taftan]] & other areas of Balochistan.<ref name=\"March 31\"/>\n\nStarting from 2 April, the lockdown in the province was extended until 14 April as per directions by the federal government.<ref name=\"lockdowns2\"/> On 7 April, the provincial government increased the lockdown period by adding another week, making it last until 21 April.<ref name=\"balochistan lockdown2\">{{cite news |title=Pakistan to raise testing capacity as corona cases cross 4,000 |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/04/07/daily-coronavirus-testing-capacity-to-reach-25000-by-months-end-says-umar/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Pakistan Today |date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407163403/https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/04/07/daily-coronavirus-testing-capacity-to-reach-25000-by-months-end-says-umar/ |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Provincial Finance Minister, Zahoor Buledi announced on 8 April that a tax relief of Rs1.5 billion would be given during the lockdown.<ref>[https://nation.com.pk/09-Apr-2020/balochistan-announces-rs-1-5b-tax-relief-amid-coronavirus-lockdown Balochistan announces Rs 1.5b tax relief amid coronavirus lockdown], The Nation, 9 April 2020</ref>\n\n====Khyber Pakhtunkhwa====\nThe provincial [[Government of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Government]] has closed all educational institutes until 5 April and postponed all public gatherings until further notice as a preventive measure.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://arynews.tv/en/coronavirus-fears-kp-educational-institutions-closed/|title= KP govt announces to close all educational institutions amid coronavirus fears|website= www.arynews.tv|date= 13 March 2020|access-date= 2020-03-13|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150417/https://arynews.tv/en/coronavirus-fears-kp-educational-institutions-closed/|archive-date= 14 March 2020|url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"school closures\"/> All inter-district public transport was banned for seven days on 22 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=KP Govt decides to ban all inter-districts public transport for seven days |url=http://www.radio.gov.pk/22-03-2020/kp-govt-decides-to-ban-all-inter-districts-public-transport-for-seven-days |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Radio Pakistan |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323083727/http://www.radio.gov.pk/22-03-2020/kp-govt-decides-to-ban-all-inter-districts-public-transport-for-seven-days |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The province announced a partial lockdown for three days on 23 March.<ref name=\"kp lockdown\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: KP govt announces three-day partial lockdown |url=https://arynews.tv/en/coronavirus-kp-govt-partial-lockdown/ |work=ARY News |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=15 April 2020 |archive-url= |archive-date= |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the [[Peshawar High Court]] decided to shut down all courts in the province until March 28. Only essential staff were allowed to come to courts with no more than one official in the office.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Peshawar High Court |url=https://www.peshawarhighcourt.gov.pk/image_bank/Orders/Notification_24032020.pdf |accessdate=23 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324103438/https://www.peshawarhighcourt.gov.pk/image_bank/Orders/Notification_24032020.pdf |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 27 March, screening teams were deputed at all district entry and exit points for screening of visitors of Covid-19 patients.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC5\"/>\n\nThe Chief Minister of the province [[Mahmood Khan]] announced on 26 March that the government had appointed at least 1,300 new doctors on contractual basis across the province to help stem the spread of coronavirus. The KP Public Service Commission also approved the recruitment of 635 more doctors to join the province's health force.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1543841/kp-hires-1300-contractual-doctors-to-fight-covid-19|title=KP hires 1,300 contractual doctors to fight Covid-19|website=Dawn|date=26 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331013617/https://www.dawn.com/news/1543841/kp-hires-1300-contractual-doctors-to-fight-covid-19|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the government approved a Rs32 billion stimulus economic package to provide relief to the masses and the business community amid the coronavirus crisis.<ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1544619/kp-chief-minister-announces-rs32bn-package KP chief minister announces Rs32bn package] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330173451/https://www.dawn.com/news/1544619/kp-chief-minister-announces-rs32bn-package |date=30 March 2020 }}, Dawn, 29 March 2020</ref> Provincial Information Minister Ajmal Wazir, announced at a press conference that the relief package include Rs11.4 billion benefiting 1.9 million deserving families, Rs3,000 would be given under the Ehsaas programme and Rs2,000 by the KP government. He added that the business community had also been exempted from taxes worth Rs5 billion and the provincial government had ramped up its testing capacity with 500 new diagnostics kits.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2186294/1-k-p-approves-rs11-4-billion-relief-package-ward-off-coronavirus-crisis/ K-P govt announces Rs11.4b relief package to ward off coronavirus crisis] The Express Tribune, March 28, 2020</ref>\n\nEquipment and supplies including oxygen concentrators, cardiac monitors, infusion pumps, dialysis catheter and other PPE were distributed among all districts of the province on 30 March.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC8\"/>\n\nThe Provincial Disaster Management Authority (PDMA) dispatched 50,000 N95 masks to departments involved in the fight against coronavirus in the province. A total of 8,000 surgical kits and caps were also given to the health departments, along with 750 litres of sanitizers and 5,000 testing kits.<ref name=\"March 31\">[https://www.geo.tv/latest/280043-coronavirus-updates-march-31-latest-news-on-the-coronavirus-pandemic-from-pakistan-and-around-the-world Coronavirus updates, March 31: Latest news on the coronavirus pandemic from Pakistan and around the world] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401133257/https://www.geo.tv/latest/280043-coronavirus-updates-march-31-latest-news-on-the-coronavirus-pandemic-from-pakistan-and-around-the-world |date=1 April 2020 }}, Geo News, 31 March 2020</ref> An additional 20,000 testing kits were also provided in early April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arynews.tv/en/kp-coronavirus-testing-kits/|title=Khyber Pakhtunkhwa gets 25,000 more coronavirus testing kits|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nKhyber Pakhtunkhwa (KP) traders\u2019 association Sarhad Chamber of Commerce (SCC), were not same page with the government, on one hand was concerned despite business losses on account of lock down other arm of the government cutting electricity supplies on the other hand  trading associations not willing to co-operate government's lockdown timing restrictions during  Ramzan to recoup their losses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/04/25/kp-traders-refuse-close-shops-4pm/|title=KP traders refuse to close shops at 4pm - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref>\n\n====Gilgit-Baltistan====\nOn 12 March, the region's [[Government of Gilgit-Baltistan|Government]] declared medical emergency in the province after more cases of were reported. Educational institutes were further closed until 5 April as a preventive measure.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://arynews.tv/en/medical-emergency-gilgit-baltistan-coronavirus-outbreak/|title= Medical emergency declared in Gilgit Baltistan to contain coronavirus|website=www.arynews.tv|date= 12 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref name=\"school closures\"/> Similar to Islamabad, Section 144 was also imposed on 21 March.<ref name=\"section 144\"/>\n\nThe provincial government decided to put the entire region on lockdown for an indefinite period on 22 March and suspended intercity transport services. Para-military forces were also tasked to ensure the lockdown.<ref name=\"gb lockdown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.radio.gov.pk/22-03-2020/gb-govt-decides-to-observe-lockdown-for-indefinite-period|title=GB Govt decides to observe lockdown for indefinite period|website=www.radio.gov.pk|date=22 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323083729/https://www.radio.gov.pk/22-03-2020/gb-govt-decides-to-observe-lockdown-for-indefinite-period|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, the Chinese government handed medical equipments and 10 tonnes of other goods to the Gilgit-Baltistan government to help it fight Covid-19. The equipment included five ventilators, 2,000 N95 masks, 200,000 face masks, 2,000 testing kits and medical protective kits.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/2185641/1-g-b-receives-medical-aid-china-fight-spread-coronavirus/ G-B receives medical aid from China to fight spread of coronavirus], Ihsan Dawar, 24News, March 27, 2020</ref> The same day, the government decided that all suspected travelers coming from the Taftan border would be tested for Covid-19.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC5\"/>\n\nThe local government announced that all education institutions would further remain closed till 5 April as a preventive measure.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC8\"/> On 31 March, the [[World Health Organization]] staff got involved in the regions's handling of the outbreak by providing support in terms of data management at district level.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC8\"/> Starting from 2 April, the lockdown in the region was extended until 14 April as per directions by the federal government.<ref name=\"lockdowns2\"/> On 8 April, the local government decided to extend the lockdown until 21 April.<ref name=\"gb lockdown2\">{{cite news |title=Gilgit-Baltistan extends lockdown till April 21 |url=https://www.brecorder.com/2020/04/08/587539/gilgit-baltistan-extends-lockdown-till-april-21/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Business Recorder |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Azad Kashmir====\nOn 14 March, the local [[Government of Azad Kashmir|Government]] declared a health emergency after a meeting of the [[National Security Council (Pakistan)|National Security Council]]. It also announced closure of educational institutions until 6 April and secondary examinations were postponed. AJK Prime Minister [[Raja Farooq Haider]] also stated that screening mechanisms were installed at all 11 points of entry while quarantine facilities were being established in all 10 districts.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health emergency imposed across Azad Jammu Kashmir amid coronavirus fears |url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/pakistan/2020/03/health-emergency-imposed-across-azad-jammu-kashmir-amid-coronavirus-fears/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Samaa |date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322192843/https://www.samaa.tv/news/pakistan/2020/03/health-emergency-imposed-across-azad-jammu-kashmir-amid-coronavirus-fears/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 21 March, a suspension of all inter-provincial transport for three days was imposed. No public transport vehicles were allowed to either enter or leave the province. It warned that violators would be punished under the Epidemic Diseases Act.<ref>{{cite news |title=AJK Suspends Inter-provincial Transport For Three Days Amid Coronavirus Fears |url=https://www.urdupoint.com/en/business/ajk-suspends-inter-provincial-transport-for-t-870620.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Urdu Point |date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322160411/https://www.urdupoint.com/en/business/ajk-suspends-inter-provincial-transport-for-t-870620.html |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, The AJK Prime Minister announced a 3-week lockdown for the region. Movement was restricted and special passes were issued for journalists and people travelling under inevitable circumstances while only one person from each family was allowed to go out to get food essentials.<ref name=\"ajk lockdown\">{{cite news |title=Azad Jammu and Kashmir PM announces three-week lockdown to combat virus |url=https://arynews.tv/en/azad-jammu-and-kashmir-pm-lockdown/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=ARY News |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323154151/https://arynews.tv/en/azad-jammu-and-kashmir-pm-lockdown/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nTwo virology labs at Abbas Institute of Medical Sciences in Muzaffarabad started PCR testing for COVID-19 on 30 March.<ref name=\"MoNHSRC8\"/> Starting from 2 April, the lockdown in the region was extended until 14 April as per directions by the federal government.<ref name=\"lockdowns2\"/>\n\n====Islamabad====\nOn 21 March, the city administration imposed Section 144 on the region for 15 days. All restaurants and shopping malls were ordered to be closed and violators could face legal consequences.<ref name=\"section 144\">{{cite news |title=Section 144 imposed in Islamabad amid rising coronavirus cases |url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/278525-section-144-imposed-in-islamabad-as-precautionary-measure-against-coronavirus |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Geo News |date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322160232/https://www.geo.tv/latest/278525-section-144-imposed-in-islamabad-as-precautionary-measure-against-coronavirus |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The local Union Council in the Bhara Kahu region was sealed after 11 suspected cases emerged from there on 23 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=UC of Islamabad being sealed after 11 coronavirus suspects emerge |url=https://arynews.tv/en/uc-of-islamabad-being-sealed/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=ARY News |date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323133604/https://arynews.tv/en/uc-of-islamabad-being-sealed/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the national government shut the outpatient departments of hospitals in the capital territory to stem the spread of the virus, only the emergency services remained optional. The capital's Deputy Commissioner, Hamza Shafqat issued a notification declaring 'a complete ban on intra-city, inter-district and inter-province movement of people by public transport. However, the metro bus service will be functional but at a distance of one seat between passengers.' Furthermore, gatherings of all kinds at public and private places were banned no one was allowed to move out of their respective union councils.<ref name=\"islamabad measures\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19:Pakistani hospitals suspend outpatient clinics |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19pakistani-hospitals-suspend-outpatient-clinics/1778600 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Anadolu Agency |date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325102005/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/covid-19pakistani-hospitals-suspend-outpatient-clinics/1778600 |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Starting from 2 April, the lockdown in the region was extended until 14 April as per directions by the federal government.<ref name=\"lockdowns2\"/>\n\n==Impact==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Politics===\nOn 15 March, in video conference of [[SAARC]] nations on coronavirus issue, country's State Minister of Health Zafar Mirza urged India for immediate lifting of the lockdown in [[India occupied Kashmir]] to allow virus containment measures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/20-Mar-2020/coronavirus-pakistan-asks-india-to-lift-blockade-in-held-kashmir|title=Coronavirus: Pakistan asks India to lift blockade in Held Kashmir|date=20 March 2020|website=The Nation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pakistan-uses-saarc-video-conference-on-coronavirus-to-raise-kashmir-calls-for-lifting-of-lockdown/articleshow/74640486.cms|title=Pakistan uses SAARC video conference on coronavirus to raise Kashmir, calls for lifting of 'lockdown'|date=15 March 2020|via=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, Prime Minister [[Imran Khan]] urged the United States President [[Donald Trump]] to temporarily lift sanctions on Iran. He stated on Twitter, 'I want to appeal to President Trump on humanitarian grounds to lift the [[Sanctions against Iran|sanctions]] against Iran till the COVID-19 pandemic is over.'<ref>[https://nation.com.pk/22-Mar-2020/pakistani-pm-khan-urges-us-to-lift-sanctions-on-iran Pakistani PM Khan urges US to lift sanctions on Iran] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328015516/https://nation.com.pk/22-Mar-2020/pakistani-pm-khan-urges-us-to-lift-sanctions-on-iran |date=28 March 2020 }} The Nation, 22 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe same day, the Foreign Minister [[Shah Mehmood Qureshi]] raised the issue of external debt faced by the country and how it should be relieved in repayment of loans on the phone with [[Heiko Maas]], the German Foreign Minister. Qureshi reportedly told Maas that united efforts were required for dealing with the pandemic and that debt relief could help Pakistan in better handling of the outbreak in the country. He further stated that sanctions on [[Iran]] should be lifted immediately so it could utilise its own resources to fight the ongoing outbreak there. In response, Maas assured him that the issues would be raised at the forthcoming [[G7]] meeting and the [[European Union]] Foreign Ministers\u2019 Conference next week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1542810/pakistan-seeks-debt-relief-to-fight-covid-19|title=Pakistan seeks debt relief to fight Covid-19|website=www.dawn.com|date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322060644/https://www.dawn.com/news/1542810/pakistan-seeks-debt-relief-to-fight-covid-19|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He also echoed the need to lift sanctions on Iran on calls with the French Foreign Minister [[Jean-Yves Le Drian]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mofa.gov.pk/foreign-minister-holds-telephone-conversation-with-foreign-minister-jean-yves-le-drian-of-france-on-the-covid-19-pandemic/|title=Foreign Minister holds telephone conversation with Foreign Minister Jean-Yves Le Drian of France on the COVID-19 Pandemic|website=www.mofa.gov.pk|date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324095442/http://mofa.gov.pk/foreign-minister-holds-telephone-conversation-with-foreign-minister-jean-yves-le-drian-of-france-on-the-covid-19-pandemic/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the Spanish Foreign Minister [[Arancha Gonzalez]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mofa.gov.pk/foreign-minister-holds-telephone-conversation-with-foreign-minister-arancha-gonzalez-laya-of-spain-on-the-covid-19-pandemic/|title=Foreign Minister holds telephone conversation with Foreign Minister Arancha Gonzalez Laya of Spain on the Covid-19 Pandemic|website=www.mofa.gov.pk|date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324095445/http://mofa.gov.pk/foreign-minister-holds-telephone-conversation-with-foreign-minister-arancha-gonzalez-laya-of-spain-on-the-covid-19-pandemic/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> on 24 March.\n\n===Economy===\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nOn 2 April, the [[Government of Pakistan]] announced that the Pakistani economy had lost Rs2.5 trillion due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/280697-pakistan-economy-to-loose-25-trillion-due-to-coronavirus-report|title=Pakistan economy to loose 2.5 trillion due to coronavirus: report|website=www.geo.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405073529/https://www.geo.tv/latest/280697-pakistan-economy-to-loose-25-trillion-due-to-coronavirus-report|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nSome government programs were mainted through the crisis in order to keep people employed. For example, the [[Plant for Pakistan]] [[reforestation]] program was maintained through the pandemic employing 60,000 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/pakistan-virus-idled-workers-hired-plant-trees-200429070109237.html|title=Pakistan's virus-idled workers hired to plant trees|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare professionals===\nThe federal government's economic relief package also benefited the healthcare professionals in the country. It was decided that if a doctor or a paramedic died while treating coronavirus patients, they would be considered martyrs and their families would receive the package that is given to martyrs.<ref name=\"martyrs\"/>\n\nMaking a landmark, the Pakistani [[Police in Pakistan|Law enforcement]] presented the [[Guard of honour#Pakistan|Guard of honour]] as a mark of respect from 27\u201329 March to the doctors and para medical staff fighting on the front lines of the global COVID-19 outbreak across the nation in Sukkur,<ref>{{cite web|first= Fahad|last= Shabbir|url= https://thepakistanpost.net/sukkur-police-presents-guard-of-honor-to-doctors-paramedical-staff/|title= Sukkur Police presents guard of honor to doctors & paramedical staff|publisher= The Pakistan post|date= 28 March 2020|accessdate= 28 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329002320/https://thepakistanpost.net/sukkur-police-presents-guard-of-honor-to-doctors-paramedical-staff/|archive-date= 29 March 2020|url-status= live}}</ref> Quetta,<ref>{{cite web|first=Naimat|last=Khan|url=https://www.arabnews.pk/node/1648966/pakistan|title=Police present ceremonial salute to medics in Balochistan, Punjab|publisher=Arab News|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329003105/https://www.arabnews.pk/node/1648966/pakistan|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and Dera Islamil Khan.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/636367-policemen-present-guard-of-honour-to-medical-staff-at-di-khan-hospital|title= Policemen present guard of honour to medical staff at DI Khan hospital|publisher= The News|date= 29 March 2020|accessdate= 30 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329231513/https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/636367-policemen-present-guard-of-honour-to-medical-staff-at-di-khan-hospital|archive-date= 29 March 2020|url-status= live}}</ref> The medical staff of a Mayo hospital in Lahore were given a guard of honor by the Lahore police for their efforts to help Pakistan fight the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|first= Aisha|last= Mahmood|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2020/03/27/584069/watch-lahore-police-gives-guard-of-honor-to-medical-staff-combating-coronavirus/|title= Watch: Lahore police gives guard of honor to medical staff combating coronavirus|publisher= Business Recorder|date=27 March 2020 |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> Observing social distance (home-quarantined) citizens of Pakistan together with celebrities raised white flags on 27 March across Pakistan from their balconies, rooftops expressing love for the doctors and para-medics who are combating without fearing from the epidemic COVID-19 virus.<ref>{{cite web|author=News Desk|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/27/white-flag-tribute-paid-doctors-fighting-coronavirus-pakistan/|title=White flag' tribute paid to doctors fighting coronavirus in Pakistan|publisher=Pakistan Today|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328141422/https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/03/27/white-flag-tribute-paid-doctors-fighting-coronavirus-pakistan/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Government of Punjab announced a one-month honorarium for the healthcare workers at the end of March. This meant that in case a healthcare worker lost their life, a martyr package was included in the regional government's relief package. Medical professionals across the province were also provided with one-month additional salary in recognition of their services.<ref name=\"punjab relief\"/><ref name=\"punjab relief2\"/>\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' interviewed a doctor, who said that the country's mishandling of the outbreak to be \"depressing and disturbing\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan coronavirus camp: 'No facilities, no humanity'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/19/pakistan-coronavirus-camp-no-facilities-no-humanity|newspaper=The Guardian|date=19 March 2020|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407190958/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/19/pakistan-coronavirus-camp-no-facilities-no-humanity|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Doctors in Pakistan have complained about the lack of personal protection equipment (PPE) required to deal with the coronavirus, and that without protection doctors have become infected and in turn were infecting other patients.<ref name=\"guardian09042020\"/> On 6 April, police broke up protests in [[Quetta]] by more than 100 doctors, who were demanding better safety equipment. Police arrested 53 doctors involved in these protests,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/06/pakistan-arrests-doctors-protest-lack-coronavirus-safety-equipment|title=Pakistan arrests doctors protesting over lack of virus safety equipment|newspaper=The Guardian|date=6 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407174034/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/06/pakistan-arrests-doctors-protest-lack-coronavirus-safety-equipment|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and doctors reported being \"beaten and humiliated\" by the police.<ref name=\"guardian09042020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/09/pakistan-doctors-beaten-police-despair-untreatable-pandemic |title=Pakistan doctors beaten by police as they despair of 'untreatable' pandemic | authors=Hannah Ellis-Petersen Shah Meer Baloch|date= 9 April 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===Sport===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports#Cricket}}\nFears of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]] spreading alarmed the [[Government of Sindh|Sindh provincial government]], who announced on 13 March that remaining matches of the [[2020 Pakistan Super League|2020 Pakistan Super League (PSL)]], scheduled in [[Karachi]], would be played [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2174849/1-coronavirus-fears-psl-matches-karachi-played-empty-stadium/|title=Covid-19: PSL matches in Karachi to be played in empty stadium|website=www.tribune.com.pk|date=12 March 2020|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312225453/https://tribune.com.pk/story/2174849/1-coronavirus-fears-psl-matches-karachi-played-empty-stadium/|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aaj.tv/english/latest/psl-matches-in-karachi-to-be-held-without-the-crowd/|title=PSL matches in Karachi to be held without the crowd|publisher=Aaj News|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2020/03/13/579762/coronavirus-psl-matches-in-lahore-to-be-played-behind-closed-doors/|title=Coronavirus: PSL matches in Lahore to be played behind closed doors|date=13 March 2020|publisher=Business Recorder|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> Similarly, [[Pakistan Cricket Board|Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB)]] offered international players participating in PSL to leave for their home countries (if they wish so), while PSL continues as per schedule.<ref>{{Cite web|title=PCB offers international players to return home|url=https://jang.com.pk/news/745194|website=www.jang.com.pk|language=Urdu|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313154214/https://jang.com.pk/news/745194|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 10 international players and one international staff member opted to leave the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1540607|title=PCB cuts short PSL after some foreign players opt to leave Pakistan over coronavirus|last=Ghaffar|first=Abdul|date=2020-03-13|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313183649/https://www.dawn.com/news/1540607|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[2020 Pakistan Super League Final|Final match]] in [[Lahore]], was rescheduled to 18 March instead of 22 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/628633-coronavirus-scare-pcb-reschedules-psl-2020-final-to-be-played-on-march-18|title=Coronavirus scare: PCB reschedules PSL 2020, final to be played on March 18|date=2020-03-13|website=The News International|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313152441/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/628633-coronavirus-scare-pcb-reschedules-psl-2020-final-to-be-played-on-march-18|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2020, the knockout fixtures (both Semi Finals and Final) of Pakistan Super League (PSL) were indefinitely postponed due to the sudden spike in coronavirus cases in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geosuper.tv/amp/4433-pcb-decides-to-call-off-psl-2020-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-report|title=PCB 'postpones' PSL 2020 amid coronavirus outbreak|publisher=Geo Super|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322135239/https://www.geosuper.tv/amp/4433-pcb-decides-to-call-off-psl-2020-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-report|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28914779/psl-called-semi-final-day|title=PSL play-offs postponed amid coronavirus fears|work=ESPNCricinfo|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317082749/https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28914779/psl-called-semi-final-day|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter six years, when [[Football Federation League|Pakistan Football Federation League]] returned, the matches were played before 16 March 2020. On 16 March 2020, the [[Pakistan Football Federation]] released a notification announcing that the matches were postponed.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe Federal Minister for Inter Provincial Coordination Dr. [[Fehmida Mirza]] on 30 March announced to create fund to cover all medical expenses of sports persons infected with COVID-19 in Pakistan.<ref name=\"sports fund\">[https://www.radio.gov.pk/30-03-2020/fehmida-announces-to-create-fund-for-sports-persons Fehmida announces to create fund for sports persons], Radio Pakistan, 30 March 2020</ref>\n\n===Religion===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\nSocial distancing being important step to be followed by all to combat COVID-19 pandemic, some of the religious activities came under critical lens in Pakistan. Returning devotees from Iran, a Tablighi Jamaat religious gathering and prayer congregations became a cause of concern due to their potential to exacerbate the outbreak in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/04/25/covid-19-ramzan-disastrous-month-pakistan/|title=COVID-19: Why Ramzan could be a disastrous month for Pakistan - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref>\n\nSome clerics took conservative position that mosques should remain open and operational during the holy month of [[Ramadan]] since congregational prayers are believed to be obligatory for Muslim men. The Minister of Science and Technology, [[Chaudhry Fawad Hussain]] expressed his disappointment over conservative stance, while the [[Pakistan Medical Association]] (PMA) along with the [[Pakistan Bar Association]] (PBA) demanded a complete lockdown in the country. The federal government upon the warning of PMA and senior doctors that relaxing the lockdown could cause a spike in the cases, decided to extend the lockdown untyil the middle of Ramadan.<ref name=\"Sigamony\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2020/04/25/592357/pbc-backs-pma-demand-to-enforce-complete-lockdown/|title=PBC backs PMA demand to enforce complete lockdown|last=Sigamony|first=Terence J.|date=2020-04-25|website=Business Recorder|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Sigamony\"/> However, permission was granted under the leadership of the President, [[Arif Alvi]] in consultation with the [[ulama]] and state representatives for Mosque congregations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mangobaaz.com/fawad-chaudhry-just-threw-major-shade-at-mufti-muneeb-honestly-it-was-pretty-savage|title=Fawad Chaudhry Just Threw Major Shade At Mufti Muneeb & Honestly, It Was Pretty Savage|last=Ahmad|first=Rameeza|date=2020-04-15|website=MangoBaaz|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/04/18/govt-allows-congregational-prayers-but-conditions-apply/|title=Govt allows Ramzan congregational prayers but conditions apply - Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2201694/1-pti-govt-ulema-agree-sops-ramazan-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=PTI govt, Ulema agree on SOPs for Ramazan amid coronavirus outbreak {{!}}|last=Virk|first=Saqib|date=19 April 2020|website=The Express Tribune|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Joseph Coutts|Cardinal Joseph Coutts]] of the [[Catholic Church]] implored the faithful to follow proper measures to prevent the spread of the coronavirus and encouraged interfaith solidarity amidst the pandemic:<ref name=\"Hussain2020\">{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Zahid |title=Virus-hit Pakistan province reaches out to Catholic community - UCA News |url=https://www.ucanews.com/news/virus-hit-pakistan-province-reaches-out-to-catholic-community/87473 |publisher=[[Union of Catholic Asian News]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318011808/https://www.ucanews.com/news/virus-hit-pakistan-province-reaches-out-to-catholic-community/87473 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{quotation|\"I also call upon my Christian brethren who would want to come to churches on Friday and Sunday to avoid large gatherings. In the end, the Almighty will reward you for your intentions. If we can\u2019t go to a church, mosque or temple, we can pray or worship at home with our families, God shall hear us. We, the people of all faiths, should pray to God to save us from this plague.\"<ref name=\"Hussain2020\"/>}}\n\n=== Unemployment===\nThe Ministry of Planning has estimated that 12.3 million to 18.5 million people will become jobless due to pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus forecast to render 18.5m jobless in Pakistan |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2189904/2-coronavirus-forecast-render-18-5m-jobless/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=The Express Tribune |date=3 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n\nThe table and graphs below are according to the live tracker of the government and are updated at the end of the day, at 12 AM [[Pakistan Standard Time|PST]] daily.\n<!-- \n********************************************